<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korea's Trade Deficit Narrows in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, June 2 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's trade deficit in May
narrowed to 686 million U.S. dollars, the lowest level in 11
months, said the Ministry of Trade, Industry and Energy today.
</P>
<P>
The ministry officials attributed the deficit fall to an export
rise for the second consecutive month and a decline trend in
imports.
</P>
<P>
May exports rose 3.9 percent from a year ago to 11.67 billion
dollars on a custom-cleared basis.
</P>
<P>
Last month, semiconductor exports, which have been the main
reason behind the trade deficits, amounted to 1,493 million
dollars, an increase of 8.8 percent from a year ago, while
non-semiconductor exports also grew 3.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The exporters should further step up efforts to enhance their
competitive edge, said Kim Dong-soo, director at the ministry's
export division
</P>
<P>
However, the five-month trade gap widened to 9,557 million
dollars, exceeding 68 percent of the projected 14 billion dollars
for the whole year, said the ministry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970603.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Construction Spending Declines in April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 2 (xinhua) -- Construction spending in the
U.S. dropped by 1 percent in April, the worst showing in this
year, the U.S. Commerce Department reported today.
</P>
<P>
The department said that construction spending in April totaled
a seasonally adjusted 596.9 billion dollars at an annual rate in
April, compared to a rate of 603.1 billion in March.
</P>
<P>
The 1 percent drop matched a similar decline in December and
was the biggest fall since a 1.1 percent decrease in May 1996.
</P>
<P>
The decline was led by a 2.6 percent drop in non-residential
commercial construction, the worst performance since a 3 percent
drop in December.
</P>
<P>
However, the residential construction edged up a slight 0.2
percent in April to an annual rate of 258.2 billion dollars, an
all-time high.
</P>
<P>
The spending on single-family construction also increased by
0.1 percent to a record 160.1 billion dollars. There was also a
gain in spending for remodeling and additions. These increases
helped offset a slight drop in apartment construction.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the weakness in commercial construction,
spending on government projects also fell in April, dropping by
1.8 percent to an annual rate of 146.7 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
It was the biggest setback since a 3.6 percent drop last
December. Spending for schools, conservation projects and water
treatment plants all fell during the month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
