<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese FM Meets With Latvian Foreign Ministry Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier and Foreign
Minister Qian Qichen, meeting today with Maris Riekstinsh, State
Secretary of the Latvian Foreign Ministry, called Latvia an
important country in the Baltic region and said that China
attaches great importance to developing relations with it.
</P>
<P>
China is pleased with the fact that, after a difficult period,
its relations with Latvia have developed smoothly since they
were normalized in 1994, he said.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, there has been rapid progress in China, but it
needs to make a greater effort to reach the standard of
medium-developed countries, he said, and noted that saying China
will threaten other countries with its development is totally
groundless.
</P>
<P>
He said that no matter what their politics or economy, not
every country can have the same mode, and that every nation, big
or small, strong or weak, rich or poor, has equal rights to
participate in international affairs.
</P>
<P>
Riekstinsh said he appreciates China's achievements in its
reform and opening-up and reiterated that the Latvian
government will keep to its "one China" principle in the Taiwan
issue.
</P>
<P>
On trade and economic cooperation, both sides say that the two
governments are taking active steps to promote bilateral trade
and economic cooperation, including direct contacts between
Chinese and Latvian entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
Riekstinsh conveyed the regards of Latvian Foreign Minister
Valdis Birkvs to Qian, who asked Riekstinsh to extend his respects
to Birkvs and said that he is expecting him to visit China.
</P>
<P>
Riekstinsh and his party arrived in Beijing yesterday for a
five-day visit at the invitation of the Chinese Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, Riekstinsh and Chinese Vice-Foreign Minister
Zhang Deguang held consultations on bilateral relations and
international issues of common concern. 
</P>
</TEXT>
