<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-02 15:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Syria's Opening Borders With Iraq Undecided </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Syrian Foreign Minister Farouq
al-Shara said today that whether to open borders between his
country and Iraq for trade is yet to be decided.
</P>
<P>
"No decision on this matter had been taken as yet," said Shara
before leaving for home at the end of a brief visit here today.
During their few-hour stay in Cairo, the foreign minister and
Syrian Vice President Abdel Halim Khaddam held talks with Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi side has reportedly taken measures to prepare for the
opening of borders to accommodate goods and items to be imported
from Syria.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Trade Minister Mohammed Mehdi Saleh told a press
conference in Baghdad Sunday that an announcement on the opening
of the borders will be made soon, indicating improved ties between
the two countries since Baghdad severed ties with Damascus in 1980
when Syria sided with Iran in the 1980-88 Iran-Iraq War.
</P>
<P>
Before departure, Shara dismissed as untrue a report recently
published by the Israeli "Maariv" that Syria had given up its
insistence on Israel's full withdrawal from the Golan Heights,
captured by the Jewish state in 1967.
</P>
<P>
"Syria says that the issue of full withdrawal to the June 4
1967 lines is part of many elements that lead to full and just
peace in the region," he added.
</P>
<P>
Syria, an important partner in the Mideast peace process, began
negotiations with Israel in 1991. But the sporadic talks broke off
last February after a spate of suicidal bomb attacks in Israel
blamed on Palestinian extremists.
</P>
<P>
Syria refused to return to the negotiating table unless the
Israeli government first agrees to a full pullout.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu rejected the demand,
saying that the strategic plateau is vital to Israel. But his
predecessors, Labor Party leaders reportedly verbally accepted an
Israeli withdrawal from the Golan in return for normalized ties
with Syria.
</P>
<P>
Syria and Egypt have been in close coordination in restarting
the Israeli-Syrian peace talks that have been frozen for over one
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
