<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Economy Maintains Momentum in 1st Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian economy maintained its
momentum in the first quarter of 1997, Statistics Canada reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Its gross domestic product advanced 0.8 percent during the
first three months of the year, following similar gains in the
previous two quarters.
</P>
<P>
Healthy gains were recorded in business investment in plant and
equipment, consumer spending and investment in housing, the
federal agency said.
</P>
<P>
"Exports rebounded from their stall in the fourth
quarter. Imports increased sharply in tandem however, feeding both
domestic demand and intermediate imputs to export production," the
agency said.
</P>
<P>
Businesses continued to increase their inventories but at a
slower pace than in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
In the first quarter, investment in plant and equipment rose
4.8 percent following back-to-back gains in the previous two
quarters of 5.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, consumer spending surged 1.3 percent, slightly
less than the previous quarter. And corporate profits advanced 4.0
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
