<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan not interfering in Afghan Affairs: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Foreign Minister Gohar
Ayub Khan told the Senate today that Pakistan was not interfering
in the internal affairs of Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
In response to a question about a press report that Russia had
threatened Pakistan on its alleged involvement in Afghan affairs,
Ayub Khan said the Pakistani Foreign Ministry "received no threat
from any country including Russia."
</P>
<P>
Instead, he added, Russian Deputy Foreign Minister will be
visiting Pakistan from June 6 to 8 and he himself is also going to
Russia on July 8.
</P>
<P>
The news report was "highly speculative" and was not based on
reality, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Afghan Taliban militia are now controlling 90 percent of
the Afghan territory and fighting is going on only in
Mazar-e-Sharif, the northern strategic town, according to the
Foreign Minister.
</P>
<P>
Talks between the Taliban and General Abdul Malik were under
way to try to arrive at an agreement, Ayub Khan said.
</P>
<P>
The situation was not alarming and it would improve, he added.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
