<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kazakhstan, Uzbekistan Keen to Expand Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA ATA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Kazakhstan and Uzbekistan should
expand cooperation and halt the fall in bilateral trade caused by
red tape, Kazakh President Nursultan Nazarbayev and his visiting
Uzbek counterpart, Islam Karimov, said today.
</P>
<P>
Karimov arrived here today for a two-day visit, the first by a
Uzbek head of state since the two countries established diplomatic
relations in November 1992.
</P>
<P>
Trade and economic cooperation was one of the main topics on
the agenda. Trade volume between the two countries fell 30
percent last year, from 423 million U.S. dollars in 1995 to 293
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders agreed that the decline was a result of
bureaucratic practices by officials in both countries.
</P>
<P>
As for integration between countries in the Commonwealth of
Independent States, the two presidents said the process should be
based on the principles of mutual respect for territorial
integrity and sovereignty and non-interference in each other's
internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
The two countries also signed 14 agreements covering free
trade, environmental protection and cooperation in transport and
telecommunications. 
</P>
</TEXT>
