<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Launches Clean-Up Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus today launched a "Clean-up
Cyprus" campaign, aimed at making the island a more competitive
tourist destination.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a launching ceremony today, President Glafcos
Clerides said "a clean Cyprus is essential for our tourism, as
well as for our own well-being."
</P>
<P>
He said, "A clean environment is an element of culture and our
tradition is obliging us to display our culture."
</P>
<P>
He also stressed the need to familiarize citizens with it,
from their early childhood.
</P>
<P>
The all-Cyprus clean-up campaign, the first phase of which
will cost 150,000 Cyprus pounds (about 300,000 U.S. dollars), is
part of new policy on tourism, approved by the Cabinet last
year, in an effort to improve the tourist environment.
</P>
<P>
Measures to be taken during the campaign include checking
up hotel operating costs, control on the number of hotel beds
and infrastructure projects and cleaning of main roads and
public places.
</P>
<P>
The campaign, to be carried out in three phases, will be
participated by municipalities and regional authorities in the
tourism areas.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, this eastern Mediterranean island attracted about
2 million foreign tourists, earning 780 million Cyprus pounds
(1.56 billion U.S. dollars). This represents 36.8 percent of the
total revenue of the country from exporting goods and services.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
