<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Socialists, Communists Negotiate Forming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The Socialist Party and the Communist
Party are negotiating the forming of a new leftwing government
after the left alliance won a parliament majority in the
legislative election.
</P>
<P>
Communist Party National Secretary Robert Hue said today that
his party is waiting for a response from the Socialist Party on
its proposals on guaranteed minimum wage, or SMIC, and budget
policies of the new government.
</P>
<P>
Hue reaffirmed his party's readiness to make a successful
leftwing government in a letter sent today to Socialist Party
First Secretary Lionel Jospin, who has been nominated prime
minister by President Jacques Chirac.
</P>
<P>
The Communist Party has proposed a 500 franc (80 U.S. dollar)
raise of the SMIC on July 1, a subsidy for helping the small and
medium-sized enterprises, a reduction of tax, and the cutting of
weekly working time from 39 hours to 35 hours without reducing
salary.
</P>
<P>
The Socialist Party, which won 240 seats in the 577-seat
National Assembly, must ally with the Communist Party, which won
38 seats, and other smaller leftwing parties to form an absolute
parliament majority and a government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
