<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa's First Ladies Urged to Promote Peace, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Incoming Chairman of the Organisation
of African Unity (OAU), Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe today
urged Africa's first ladies to promote peace and stability in the
continent.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe, who had just taken over the leadership of the 53-member
organisation from Cameroun President Paul Biya, said the continent's
first ladies should assist in ensuring that the political environment
in their countries was conducive to peace, stability and
humanitarianism.
</P>
<P>
He was responding to an address to the OAU summit by Mariam
Abacha, wife of Nigerian leader General Sani Abacha, who
presented him with the report of the first summit of the African
first ladies peace mission held in Abuja, Nigeria, last May.
</P>
<P>
Madame Abacha, who chairs the peace mission and is the first
African first lady to address the OAU in its 34-year history, had
asked African leaders attending the summit to deal seriously with
issues of conflicts, wars and refugees that bedevil Africa and affect
mostly women and children.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe thanked the African first ladies for coming up with the
initiative, saying it was timely and deserved the support of african
leaders in the pursuit of the common objective of achieving peace and
unity on the continent which has a record six million refugees and 20
million displaced people.
</P>
<P>
He added that African first ladies had a serious task to ensure
that ''first gentlemen'' worked in a political environment that
guaranteed peace, observance of human rights and democratic rule.
</P>
<P>
''First ladies must assist in the promotion of democracy and
ensure that dictators are brought to book,'' said Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
''They can build a very, very strong whip and let them use it
because behind every successful man there is a woman and behind
every successful first gentleman, there is a first lady,'' he
said. enditem

=06021639

=06021934
NNNN
00:42 00:43 g # PAB
</P>
