<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-02 16:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Raps PA Over Killing of Land Dealers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Israeli government decided today
to lodge a sharp protest to the Palestinian Authority (PA) over
its alleged involvement in murdering Palestinians who sold land to
Jews.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made at a meeting of Israeli security
establishment convened by Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu,
Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai and Public Security Minister
Avigdor Kahalani.
</P>
<P>
The meeting condemned the PA for the recent killing of
three Palestinians who sold land to Jews, and ordered the
police and security services to take measures to prevent
further kidnapping and murder of Palestinian land dealers.
</P>
<P>
The General Security Service has compiled a list of
Palestinian land dealers for security protection. Meanwhile, the
police will issue arrest warrants to suspects in the murders.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu claimed that police investigations have indicated the
PA's involvement in the killing of three Palestinian land
dealers. Warning the incidents are hurting the peace process,
Netanyahu vowed that his government will "do all it can to
fight the phenomenon."
</P>
<P>
To increase pressure on the PA, Netanyahu said Israel is
working to arrange an international forum to discuss what he
called PA's violations of human rights and peace accords.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after attending the Knesset (Parliament) Foreign
Affairs and Defense Committee to brief the security situation,
Mordechai once against blamed the PA for the recent killings.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai said Israel would not allow the continuation of
such acts and would do its best to prevent more killings.
He also called on the international community to take actions
to pressure the PA to stop killing land delaers.
</P>
<P>
Israel's angry reaction came after the third Palestinian land
dealer was found killed last Saturday in the
Palestinian-controlled city of Ramallah, north to the Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Ali Jamhour, 34, the Palestinian land dealer, who lived in
Jerusalem's Shuafat refugee camp and held an Israeli indentity
card, was shot twice in the head.
</P>
<P>
Two weeks ago, Farid Bashiti, a 70-year-old Palestinian land
dealer living in Jerusalem, was also shot dead in Ramallah,
becoming the first victim of recent wave of killings. Days
later, another land dealer named Harbi Abu Sarah from a
village near Ramallah, was also killed reportedly for selling
land to Israelis.
</P>
<P>
Last Saturday night, Jerusalem police also foiled an attempt
by six Palestinians to abduct Palestinian land dealer Assad
Rajibi, who is living in northeast of the city.
</P>
<P>
The Police pursued the two cars driven by the kinappers
on the road to Ramallah, and stopped them after a 15
minute chase. Rajibi was freed and the six kidnappers were
arrested. Four of the six men were claimed by Israeli police
to be Palestinian security agents.
</P>
<P>
Israel blames the recent wave of killings on the PA
because they all occured following the PA cabinet meeting last
month calling for punishment of those who sell land to
Jews, as part of its fight against Israel's settlement
expansion.
</P>
<P>
PA Justice Minister Freih Abu Meidein has said that selling
land to Jews was punishable by the death penalty. But he denied
today any PA involvement in the recent killings, and blasted
Israel for interfering in the PA's internal politics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
