<HEADLINE> Arafat Seeks Support in Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian President Yasser Arafat
today urged African countries to support his organization's
stance against "expropriation of Palestinian land" by the Israeli
government of Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening session of the 33rd summit of the
Organization of African Unity, Arafat said the Israeli government
is currently involved in the violation of human rights through
the occupation of Palestinian land in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
He said Israel, by constructing resettlements on Palestinian
land, is violating the United Nations resolution 181 on Palestine
and also threatening the process of attaining peace in the Middle
East.
</P>
<P>
The Resolution 181, Arafat said, was reached when 134 countries
voted in favor of it while only three opposed it, and for that
reason it was not proper for the Netanyahu government to breach
it.
</P>
<P>
"I would like to assure you of our commitment to negotiations
and peace to ensure the rights of our people," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We invite you to urge Israel to commit itself to the
attainment of peace and stop the expropriation of Palestine
land," he said.
</P>
<P>
The OAU is expected to adopt a resolution supporting the
Palestinian people and the right to their land as well as
condemning the Israeli government for violating the principles on
which the Middle East peace process is founded.
</P>
<P>
Arafat said it is only through the attainment of peace that
the entire Middle East region could prosper and develop. 
</P>
</TEXT>
