<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Women to Play Bigger Role in New French Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Women will play a bigger role in the
newly elected French parliament as the number of women deputies
has almost doubled to 63 from the 32 of the previous parliament.
</P>
<P>
Mainly due to the success of women candidates from leftwing
parties, women's representation rate in the French parliament has
increased to 10.9 percent from 6.4 percent, the highest in the
history of the Fifth Republic.
</P>
<P>
The Socialist Party, which let its women candidates to run in
30 percent of the constituencies, has had 42 women candidates
elected or re-elected this time.
</P>
<P>
The Communist Party's women deputies also increased from two in
the previous parliament to four, all elected or re-elected in the
Paris region.
</P>
<P>
The Green Party, which entered parliament for the first time,
had three out of seven elected as women deputies.
</P>
<P>
Seven out of eight outgoing women deputies of the Gaullist
Rally for the Republic were re-elected this time, while the
centrist Union of French Democracy saw only five of its 17
outgoing women deputies surviving in the new parliament.
</P>
<P>
But France still falls behind many European countries in women
representation in parliament, such as Britain whose parliament has
an 18.2 percent women representation, Italy with 12.7 percent,
Spain with 30 percent, Sweden with 40 percent, and Iceland with 50
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
