<HEADLINE> Syrian High-Ranking Officials to Visit Beirut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese President Elias Hrawi
announced here today that Syrian Vice President Abdul-Halim
Khaddam and Foreign Minister Farouk al-Shara will visit Beirut in
the next 48 hours to brief him on the outcome of their recent
tour of Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
Hrawi told visitors to the Beirut Presidential Palace that
Khaddam and Shara will be in Beirut "Tuesday or Wednesday" to
inform him of regional situations and Arab affairs, especially
after the Turkish incursion into northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese president, quoted by the state-run Lebanese
National News Agency, stressed that every Arab state has a
link with "the Turkish aggression against Iraq."
</P>
<P>
The two Syrian officials have been leading a massive
diplomatic drive in an attempt to rally Arab and international
support for the Syrian position in the deadlocked Middle East
peace process.
</P>
<P>
Syria has sensed U.S. and Israeli schemes to isolate it from
peace process by concentrating on the Israeli-Palestinian track
and by developing U.S.-backed military cooperation between Turkey
and Israel, local reports said.
</P>
<P>
During their latest tour of Arab states in the Gulf and
North Africa, the Syrian officials sought to alert Arab
leaders to the dangers of this so-called "Turkish-Israeli-U.S.
alliance" in the hope of prompting a common Arab strategy to
deal with it.
</P>
<P>
They also sought to persuade and bring Arab pressure to
bear on the Gulf state of Qatar to postpone a Middle East
and North African economic summit in Doha in November.
</P>
<P>
According to the reports, Syria believes the holding of such
conference with Israel's participation would "undermine Arab
resolutions adopted a year ago to stop all normalization moves
with Israel." 
</P>
</TEXT>
