<HEADLINE> Roundup: OAU Moves On to Eradicate Child Labor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Yu Dabo)
</P>
<P>
HARARE, June 2 (Xinhua) -- African leaders meeting here at
their 33rd summit today stressed the urgent need to protect
African children from forced labor.
</P>
<P>
Salim Ahmed Salim, secretary general of the Organization of
African Unity (OAU), devoted much attention to the issues of
child labor and frequent use of children as combatants in his
report presented to the summit.
</P>
<P>
The OAU summit opened today at the Sheraton Hotel in downtown
Harare amid intensifying efforts by the organization to address a
series of issues facing the African continent.
</P>
<P>
Unlike previous summits, this year's meeting placed the
protection of children high on the agenda. The summit followed
the International Children's Day.
</P>
<P>
Child labor is a complicated and widespread problem in many
developing countries, particularly in Africa, where work by
children is commonplace and perceived to be firmly rooted in
socio-cultural and economic factors.
</P>
<P>
In many households and factories across Africa, especially in
rural areas, child work forms an integral part of children's
upbringing and training towards adulthood and is considered an
important part of the child's socialization process.
</P>
<P>
Studies by the OAU on agricultural plantations in a number of
African countries offered clear evidence of risk to children from
pesticides and chemicals, heavy machinery, harsh climatic
conditions and sustained period of overwork. Moreover, these
child laborers earn little or no pay.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970603.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
