<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: OAU Moves On to Eradicate Child Labor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Yu Dabo)
</P>
<P>
HARARE, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The widespread child labor has
drawn serious concern from the OAU, and OAU officials said
African governments are anxious to address these and other abuses
stemming from child labor.
</P>
<P>
The OAU summit is expected to take a coherent
multi-disciplinary approach which focuses on key issues like
education, the enactment and enforcement of legislation, and the
underlying problem of poverty alleviation.
</P>
<P>
The conference will also demonstrate a firm political will at
the highest level to eradicate child labor, OAU officials said.
</P>
<P>
They said the OAU is currently joining a broad cooperative
effort involving UNICEF and other UN agencies, national
governments, workers' and employers' organizations to solve the
child labor problem.
</P>
<P>
To meet the challenge, the OAU is set to provide assistance in
the design and implementation of programs for the protection of
children and the phased elimination of child labor.
</P>
<P>
It has been rapidly expanding its activities on the continent,
sponsoring workshops and conferences with the aim of stimulating
greater debate, expertise, analysis and action at national and
regional levels.
</P>
<P>
Pilot surveys for the development of a methodology to gather
fresh and more reliable data on child labor have been undertaken,
and a series of localized action programs launched.
</P>
<P>
These programs include activities ranging from
awareness-raising and advocacy, to the improvement of labor
inspection methods. So far, 15 African countries have played host
to these project activities.
</P>
<P>
As the world is stepping up its efforts for the protection of
children, the OAU seeks to provide a forum for dialogue. The
current OAU summit offers the possibility of an important step
forward. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970603.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
