<HEADLINE> Deposed Afghan PM to Form Anti-Taliban Front With </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Deposed Afghan prime minister
Gulbuddin Hekmatyar has decided to form a joint front with Uzbek
general Abdul Malik to fight against the Islamic Taliban militia,
Afghan sources said today.
</P>
<P>
Hekmatyar, who was ousted last September when the Taliban took
Kabul, said in an interview that he would consolidate with Malik
in fighting against the Islamic militia, according to the sources
in Peshawar, Pakistan's major city in the northwestern region.
</P>
<P>
Malik, whose defection triggered the downfall of his former
boss Uzbek warlord Rashid Dostum, turned his back on the Taliban
late last month almost immediately after the fall of
Mazar-e-Sharif, Dostum's headquarters, causing a serious setback
for the Taliban in northern Afghan fronts.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the sources said, fighting between the Taliban and
opposition forces including those of Malik and Ahamd Masood, the
former military chief of the ousted Afghan government, was
continuing in the northern provinces of Samangan, Baghlan, Parwan
and Wardak.  
</P>
