<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Calls for More Aid for Palestinian Refugees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Jordan today called on donor nations
to continue bearing their responsibility for Palestinian refugees
and increase donations to the United Nations Relief and Work Agency
(UNRWA).
</P>
<P>
The appeal was made by Jordan's Crown Prince Hassan today when
he was visiting a training center of the UNRWA here.
</P>
<P>
The crown prince warned that any cut on the education and
health aid by the UNRWA, which is to suffer a tight budget this
year, will adversely affect the Palestinian refugees' living
standards and will not help their cause.
</P>
<P>
The world's relief agency has rendered help to some 3 million
Palestinian refugees in Jordan, Syria, Lebanon, the West Bank and
Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
With some 1 million Palestinian refugees, about one fourth
of its total population in the kingdom, Jordan allocates 300
million U.S. dollars annually for the refugee camps, a sum close
to UNRWA's estimated annual budget of 360 million dollars,
Hassan noted.
</P>
<P>
The allocation was important in raising the living standards of
all the refugees in the Jordanian society, he added.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he said, the refugees' right to repatriation and
compensation should not be undermined.
</P>
<P>
The UNRWA is reportedly seeking more donations to ensure its
work this year.
</P>
<P>
About 1 million Palestinians were made homeless during the
First Middle East War in 1948 when Israel annexed part of the
Palestinian land.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians then went to live in the refugee camps in
Jordan, Syria, Lebanon and the Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
In the following year, the United Nations established the
UNRWA, a sister agency to the U.N. High Commissioner for
Refugees (UNHCR), to deal with the issues of the Palestinian
refugees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970603.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-02 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cypriot President: Turkey's Instability Affects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Political instability in Turkey
will affect ongoing efforts to seek a solution to Cyprus' issue,
Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides warned here today.
</P>
<P>
In a statement to the press, President Clerides said "there
will be a period of political instability in Turkey, which
cannot be helpful to efforts towards finding a Cyprus solution."
</P>
<P>
His words came just a few days before invitations can be issued
by U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan for direct talks between the
Greek and Turkish Cypriot sides. The talks were set to begin in
July near New York.
</P>
<P>
Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash have both
said they will respond positively to Annan's call for talks.
</P>
<P>
"We will attend the talks despite the fact we haven't noticed
any change in the Turkish stance on the basic aspects of the
problem, but after assurances given by the U.N. chief that he
will have the support of the five permanent members of the
Security Council," Clerides said.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot president disclosed the Greek Cypriot side told
the U.N., the U.S., Britain and France that it would attend the
talks to avoid being blamed as the "negative" side, a stance
that could affect Cyprus' bid for accession to the European
Union.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the thorny question of security, the president
said "we have already pointed out that future security is one of
the most basic issues concerning the Cyprus problem and without
finding a solution to this particular question, no Cyprus
solution can be reached."
</P>
<P>
He said the security issue has three aspects, namely the
island's complete demilitarization, the deployment of a
multi-national force with a mandate from the U.N. Security
Council to intervene when the territorial integrity, independence
or the security of one of the two communities is threatened, and
the abolition of any guarantor power's right to intervene.
</P>
<P>
Britain, Turkey and Greece have played the role of guarantors
of Cyprus after the island's independence from Britain in 1960.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus problem has remained unsolved since 1974 when the
island was divided after Turkish troops occupied its northern
third in the wake of an Athens-backed coup. 
</P>
</TEXT>
