<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Legal Center of Namibia Wins UNICEF's Award </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The Legal Assistance Center
of Namibia has won the 1997 Maurice Pate Award for its outstanding
contributions in drafting child-rights legislation in that
southwestern African nation, the United Nations Children's Fund
(UNICEF) announced today.
</P>
<P>
The annual Pate Award, the UNICEF's highest honor, is named for
the agency's first executive director who led the UNICEF from 1947
until his death in 1965.
</P>
<P>
"From the drafting of national legislation to protect children,
its community-based legal education programs, its efforts to help
adolescents stay out of trouble and assist families in need, the
center has demonstrated a dedication to children's rights that is
an inspiration not only to a region, but an entire continent,"
said Carol Bellamy, the UNICEF's executive director.
</P>
<P>
Founded in 1988, two years before Namibia gained its
independence from South Africa, the center played a pivotal role
in drafting the Children Care and Protection Act, a comprehensive
legal proposal that has been presented to Namibia's legislature,
the UNICEF reported.
</P>
<P>
Its efforts on behalf of adolescents includes the Juvenile
Justice Project, a program that works with government ministries
and other non-governmental organizations to find alternatives to
prison for young offenders. It also works to deter adolescents
from crime, according to the UNICEF. 
</P>
</TEXT>
