<HEADLINE> Tensions between Hezbollah, Peace-Keepers Ease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 2 (Xinhua) -- A spokesman of the U.N. peacekeeping
forces operating in south Lebanon said here today that the recent
problems with the Lebanese pro-Iranian Hezbollah, or Party of God,
were over.
</P>
<P>
Timur Goksel, who is also the political advisor of the
U.N. Interim Force in Lebanon (UNIFIL), made the announcement
after meeting a leader of the Lebanese Shiite Muslim party.
</P>
<P>
Tensions erupted last week between Hezbollah and the UNIFIL
following reports that former UN trucks were being manned by
Israeli troops in the occupation zone, leading to fears of
surprise attacks by the Israeli forces.
</P>
<P>
Repeated harassments against Irish and Polish soldiers of the
U.N forces were then reported to be meted out by Hezbollah, which
vowed to fight and oust the Israeli occupation fores out of south
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Nabil Kaouk, Hezbollah's head in south Lebanon who
received the UNIFIL delegation led by Goksel in the south
Lebanese market town of Nabatiyeh, said they discussed the issue
of UN vehicles being used by Israeli forces and the measures to be
taken by the UNIFIL.
</P>
<P>
However Goksel described the reports on UN vehicles being used
by Israeli troops occupying a border strip in south Lebanon as
"exaggerated."
</P>
<P>
He promised that the UNIFIL will take measures to treat this
issue, but declined to specify.
</P>
<P>
He confirmed that some vehicles belonging to the U.N.
Disengagement Observer Force (UNDOF) on the Golan Heights had
been sold, but stressed that "they were scrap vehicles and
unusable."
</P>
<P>
Kaouk accused the Israel of violating international laws and
using all means to protect its soldiers."
</P>
<P>
The 4,500-strong UNIFIL, comprising contingents from Fiji,
Finland, France, Ghana, Ireland, Italy, Nepal, Norway and
Poland, was set up in 1978 in south Lebanon following the
first Israeli aggression of that country.
</P>
<P>
A UNIFIL statement had complained that in a Friday incident,
two Irish soldiers were disarmed and ordered to lie on the road
after their UN vehicle were stopped by five armed Hezbollah
fighters.
</P>
<P>
In another incident on Thursday, seven Hezbollah gunmen
stopped two Polish UNIFIL soldiers, placed guns to the their heads
and pulled triggers of empty chambers, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
South Lebanese security sources said that a number of scrapped
UN trucks belonging to the UNDOF had been sold to a south
Lebanese businessman from Marjayoun, and the trucks were
transported to Marjayoun via Israel.
</P>
<P>
Goksel pointed out that this was not the first time for the
multi-national peacekeeping forces to face problems in their
20-year-old presence in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
"The presence of the neutral international forces is for
safeguarding the residents, helping and pacifying the people,"
Goksel underlined.  
</P>
</TEXT>
