<HEADLINE> S. African Trade Union Holds General Strikes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Hundreds of thousand of
Congress of South Africa Trade Union (COSATU) members today took
to the street across the country in protest against the Basic
Conditions of Employment Bill.
</P>
<P>
COSATU leader Sam Shilowa told reporters that more than two
million workers responded to the COSATU's call for better
conditions of employment.
</P>
<P>
The employment bill adopted by Business South Africa provides
for a 45-hour working week and for four months' maternity leave,
but makes no reference to payment.
</P>
<P>
It conditionally sets the employable age limit at 15, but says
only 18-year-olds and above can be employed in jobs deemed
physical or dangerous.
</P>
<P>
However, the COSATU demands a maximum 40-hour working week and
six months' maternity leave, four months of which should be paid
leave. The labor federation also wants the employment age limit
set at 18.
</P>
<P>
Today's 24-hour general strike was the third since the 1994
general elections, aimed at forcing employers to accede to the
humble demands of workers on legislative issues pertaining to
improvement of working conditions and worker rights, Shilowa said.
</P>
<P>
He warned employers that if they wanted to take a hard line,
the union federation would also take a tit-for-tat attitude to
challenge them.
</P>
<P>
A large number of police, soldiers and traffic officials were
mobilized to maintain strong presence in central Johannesburg
when tens of thousands of demonstrators were marching in the
downtown streets.
</P>
<P>
So far, there is no report of any clashes between the police
and demonstrators. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
