<HEADLINE> Saudi Arabia Lauds Results of GCC FM Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabia today welcomed
results of the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) Foreign Ministers'
Meeting that dealt with issues of mutual interest both in the Gulf
region and the Middle East as a whole.
</P>
<P>
This came after a weekly session of the cabinet meeting
chaired by Saudi King Fahd Bin Abdul Aziz, said reports of the
Kuwait News Agency from Saudi Red Sea city of Jeddah.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministers of the six GCC states expressed the hope that
the GCC-Iranian relations would improve and called on Tehran to
end what they termed as its occupation of the three islands of Abu
Mousa, Greater and Lesser Tunbs, over which the United Arab
Emirates (UAE) also claims sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
The ministers condemned Iran's pursuit of the "status quo
policy" on the three islands, which they said constitutes a
violation of the UAE's sovereignty and undermines the regional
peace and stability.
</P>
<P>
On the Middle East peace process, the ministers also voiced
"profound" worry over its stalemate and future deterioration due
to Israel's provocative policies, mainly on building more
settlements in the occupied territories.
</P>
<P>
They denounced the Israeli "illegitimate and irresponsible"
practices, urging the Jewish state to honor the signed accords and
comply with international mandate related to the peace process.
</P>
<P>
They also called on Turkey to withdraw from northern Iraq and
stop its intervention in the internal affairs of its Arab
neighbor.
</P>
<P>
The ministers also expressed their "great worry" over the
latest Turkish military movements in northern Iraq, saying that
the intrusion will "threaten international peace and security."
</P>
<P>
In their statement, the ministers also reaffirmed their firm
stand on Iraq's full compliance with U.N. resolutions relating
to its 1990 invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The GCC, a regional political and economic bloc founded in
1981, groups Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, the UAE, Oman, Qatar and
Bahrain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
