<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study Suggests Minimum Wage Without Increasing Jobless </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 2 (Xinhua) -- A minimum wage could be introduced
at up to 3.75 pounds (six US dollars) an hour without adding to
Britain's unemployment, according to a report published today.
</P>
<P>
A study by the Employment Policy Institute (EPI) found that
Conservative claims of big job losses as a result of setting a
statutory pay floor were misplaced.
</P>
<P>
In a 10-point program for the Low Pay Commission (LPC), the
tripartite body of business, unions and academics which will work
out the details of the national minimum wage (NMW), the EPI said
attention should be focused on issues other than the hourly rate.
</P>
<P>
The LPC was announced by Labor while in opposition as a means
of moving away from the party's former commitment to a rigid
formula -- half male median earnings -- for a minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
The report will help the Labor government to fend off charges
from the Conservatives that a minimum wage at four pounds (6.4 US
dollars) an hour would cost up to a million jobs.
</P>
<P>
The EPI argued that there was no evidence to show that minimum
wages harmed employment in those sectors covered by wages councils
between the late 1970s and early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the NMW should not be seen as an
anti-poverty panacea but as part of a range of measures to help
people on low incomes.
</P>
<P>
On wage costs, the EPI stressed that a NMW would add about 1
percent to the wage bill if set at 3.80 pounds (6.1 US dollars) an
hour, but the total impact was likely to be greater because of the
impact on differentials.
</P>
<P>
Estimates have shown that a NMW of 3.25 pounds (4.2 US dollars)
an hour accompanied by 25 percent restoration of differentials
could increase the inflation rate by 0.6 percent, rising to 1.1
percent for a NMW of 3.80 pounds (6.1 US dollars) an hour.
</P>
<P>
The EPI said, "Knock-on effects are difficult to assess with
any accuracy. The LPC should as a priority obtain detailed
estimates of likely knock-on effects."
</P>
<P>
The report suggested the system should provide in-built
protection against higher youth unemployment by setting a lower
rate for younger workers and trainees.
</P>
<P>
The EPI said that the policing of the minimum wage should be
integrated with existing forms of routine business inspection to
reduce intrusiveness and unnecessary red tape. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970603.0046 </DOCNO>
