<HEADLINE> Mubarak's Sons Sue Saudi Paper for Libel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak's
two sons have filed a libel suit against a leading Saudi newspaper
which told "lies" about their business dealings, the Egyptian MENA
news agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Sharq Al-Awsat was sued for publishing a full-page
advertisement for a new magazine which promised to include a
report, complete with pictures and figures, the deals, commissions
and monopolies allegedly attributed to Alaa and Gamal Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
According to the advertisement, Alaa and Gamal will get one
million pounds as commission on every Airbus aircraft EgyptAir had
bought, said a senior prosecution source who listed the "false
allegations" by the leading Arabic daily.
</P>
<P>
The London-based paper also blamed the delayed marketing of
mobile phones in Egypt on Alaa's seeking to be the sole franchiser.
</P>
<P>
It believed that the granites slabs that the Cairo government
use to beautify the city streets were bought from the president's
son.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak's two sons, who are both prominent members of Egyptian
business groups, said the ad "included lies defaming their
characters and the reputation of their family."
</P>
<P>
The attorney general office is investigating the complaint and
defendants, a Saudi-owned media company, will be interrogated.
</P>
<P>
It was not immediately known what penalties the company might
face, but Asharq Al-Awsat daily was banned Tuesday. 
</P>
