<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Notifies Congress on Sierra Leone Evacuation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 2 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton on Monday
formally notified Congress of U.S. military moves of evacuating
Americans from Freetown, the capital of Sierra Leone, in
accordance with what he called the War Power Resolution.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to Congress, Clinton said the military moves were
taken because of risks the Americans were facing in the West
African country where a recent military coup had overthrown an
elected government.
</P>
<P>
"On May 29 and May 30, due to the uncertain security situation
and the possible threat to American citizens and the American
Embassy in sierra Leone, approximately 200 U.S. military
personnel, including an 11-member Special Forces detachment, were
positioned in Freetown to prepare for the evacuation," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the U.S. forces would leave Sierra Leone "as soon as
evacuation operations are complete and enhanced security and
location in and around Freetown is no longer required."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, White House spokesman Mike McCurry said more than
300 Americans had been evacuated from Sierra Leone and the
operation would continue for those still trapped in the country.
</P>
<P>
"We continue to monitor efforts related to remaining citizens
who are innocently trapped (by fighting)," he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
McCurry said violence were continuing in Sierra Leone and the
situation in the capital of Freetown had been deteriorating.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. embassy there was hit by rocket-propelled grenade
rounds, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
