<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Chinese Choose Cremation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 3 (Xinhua) -- More than a third of the Chinese
people adopt cremation rather than the traditional way of burial
in the ground, according to the Ministry of Civil Affairs.
</P>
<P>
The rate of cremation stands at 35.2 percent and cremation has
become a common practice in eight provinces and municipalities, or
about a third of the country, according to Doje Cering, minister
of civil affairs, citing the achievement at a national meeting on
burial ritual reform that opened here today.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, China has strengthened management on the practice of
burial in the ground, by encouraging the establishment of public
cemeteries.
</P>
<P>
China has built more than 100,000 village-level cemeteries and
nearly 200 city-level cemeteries, forsaking the tradition of
burying the dead anywhere they fancy, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the country has recovered more than 66,000 ha of
farmland through removing tombs in the farmland and along the
railways and highways.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, achievement is also seen in less wastful spending
and superstitious activities in funeral ceremonies, he said.
</P>
<P>
China has more than 2,300 funeral homes, crematoriums and
public cemeteries, which has a combined fixed assets of some 1.9
billion yuan. Over 30,000 people work in this special trade.
</P>
<P>
The minister calls on local officials to work harder in the
reform of funeral and interment, pointing out that workers in this
trade still suffer social prejudice and facilities are outdated in
some places. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
