<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Students Celebrate Hong Kong's Return To Motherland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Students from Lanzhou University
and the Chinese University of Hong Kong gathered near the "Mother
Yellow River" statue today in the capital of northwest China's
Gansu province to celebrate Hong Kong's return to the motherland.
</P>
<P>
The students from Chinese University were members of the
"Today's Silk Route" exchange delegation and brought soil from
Hong Kong's Kowloon to symbolize that area. They poured the soil
out in front of the statue to tell the Yellow River that Hong Kong
will return home soon.
</P>
<P>
People will never forget the humiliation China suffered when
the government of the Qing Dynasty ceded Hong Kong to the British
Government in 1861.
</P>
<P>
This was the first visit to northwestern China for most of the
thirty Hong Kong students and they wanted to further understand
the history of their motherland on the ancient silk route.
</P>
<P>
Four bottles of water taken from the Yellow River in Qinghai,
Gansu, Ningxia and Inner Mongolia were given to the Hong Kong
students by the students from Lanzhou University to welcome Hong
Kong's return to the motherland.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
