<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Meets With New Party Leader of Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng, meeting
with Hiroyuki Sonoda, Chief Secretary of Japan's New Party
Sakigake, said that bilateral relations will continue to develop
as long as China and Japan adhere to the principles of the
Sino-Japanese joint statement and treaty of peace and friendship
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Hiroyuki Sonoda is here to attend a seminar on Sino-Japanese
relations, organized by the China Association for International
Friendly Contacts.
</P>
<P>
Li said he hopes the seminar will contribute to mutual
understanding between the people of the two countries and to the
development of friendship and relations of cooperation., He wished
the seminar a success.
</P>
<P>
He said that on the whole, the bilateral relations have
developed smoothly since the normalization of diplomatic
relations 25 years ago.
</P>
<P>
He noted that participants in the seminar include elected
members of the two sides from the 21st Century Committee for
China-Japan Friendship.
</P>
<P>
At the time of the establishment of the committee, people
thought that the 21st century was far away. Today, the 21st
century is just ahead, he said, adding that both sides are
farsighted in setting up the significant committee.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that the committee will play an active
role in improving and coordinating exchanges by the turn of the
century and in properly handling the existing issues involving two
sides so as to provide a sound Sino-Japanese relationship for the
coming century.
</P>
<P>
This should be an important task for the committee, Li said.
</P>
<P>
Li noted that the Sonodas have been dedicated to Sino-Japanese
friendship, saying that he is glad to see that the wife of Sunao
Sonoda and several former ambassadors to China were present at the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that all the old Japanese friends will,
as always, contribute to the development of Sino-Japanese ties.
</P>
<P>
Hiroyuki Sonoda said that the seminar's purpose is to reach a
consensus, increase contact at all levels, and promote bilateral
ties.
</P>
<P>
The seminar, which opened this morning, was organized by the
China Association for International Friendly Contacts.
</P>
<P>
During the three-day seminar, more than 100 Chinese and
Japanese experts in politics, economy, diplomacy, and other areas
will discuss and evaluate bilateral relations and co-operation in
politics, economy, culture, and other fields and how to develop
the Sino-Japanese relations into the 21st century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
