<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Remembering The Burning of Opium in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, June 3 (Xinhua) -- More than 30,000 students,
officials, and other people took to the streets of Dongguan City
in south China's Guangdong Province today as 500 kg of drugs were
burned in a public demonstration.
</P>
<P>
The action took place in Dongguan's People's Park Stadium and
Humen Township People's Square to mark the 158th anniversary of
the "Opium-Burning in Humen".
</P>
<P>
That event was done by Lin Zexu, who had been sent by the
emperor to look into the problem of opium trafficking. Over 20,000
cases of opium, 1.15 million kg, were seized from British and
American traders. It was all burned at once in Humen, on June 3,
1839.
</P>
<P>
The organizers of today's demonstration said that 686 student
anti-drug groups have been set up in the city, involving a total
of local 320,000 students.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1995, there were more than 520,000 drug-users
registered in China, more than 80 percent of whom were under the
age of 35.
</P>
<P>
A government official says that increasing education about
drugs among young people is essential because they are the future
of the country and should not be harmed by drugs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
