<DOCNO> XIE19970603.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Korea Sets Up Ambitious Plan on Information Technology </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The South Korean government today
unveiled a plan aimed at making the nation one of the world's top
five information technology (IT) powerhouses within the next
decade.
</P>
<P>
Under its blueprint, the government will invest some 3.15
billion U.S. dollars in developing the domestic IT industry and
promoting an information-based society in the country.
</P>
<P>
The ambitious plan was finalized at a meeting of cabinet
ministers and heads of other government agencies, chaired by Prime
Minister Koh Kun.
</P>
<P>
The plan will work on two levels - demand and supply.
</P>
<P>
The demand side of the plan features a variety of programs to
be implemented by each ministry and government agency for a
broader application of information technology.
</P>
<P>
The programs include an integrated global diplomatic
information network by the foreign ministry, an education network
by the education ministry and a nationwide electronic ID card
system by the home affairs ministry.
</P>
<P>
On the supply side, the government will pour about 876 million
dollars next year into technological development, manpower
cultivation, the fostering of IT firms and software houses, and
assistance for domestic IT firms moving into foreign markets.
</P>
<P>
The government intends to channel 663 million dollars into
technological development with focus on such core technologies as
broadband CDMA (code division multiple access), multimedia and
new-generation rechargeable batteries.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 86 million dollars have been earmarked for human
resources development. While beefing up support for IT-related
educational institutions, the government also plans to open a
world-class graduate school specializing in information technology
in the southern city of Taejon.
</P>
<P>
Emphasis will also be put on fostering IT ventures and software
houses. To help start-up IT ventures, the government is to set up
a cooperative aimed at providing capital to those who want to
incorporate new firms based on their technological expertise.
</P>
<P>
More support centers for software designers and ASIC
(application-specific integrated circuit) developers will also be
established.
</P>
<P>
The government will help IT ventures attract and keep talented
staff by improving the present share option system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970603.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sinn Fein Barred from Northern Ireland Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The political wing of the IRA, Sinn
Fein, was again barred from multi-party talks on the future of
Northern Ireland which resumed today in Belfast.
</P>
<P>
After being blocked from entering a government building for the
talks, Sinn Fein President Gerry Adams asked angrily, "Is there
any possibility of even opening this gate so that we can have a
civilized conversation?"
</P>
<P>
Britain's new Labor government recently eased a ban on official
contacts with Sinn Fein without preconditions of a ceasefire from
the IRA, and held two rounds of talks with a Sinn Fein delegation
on the deadlocked peace process.
</P>
<P>
However, the government has refused to give a seat to Sinn Fein
at the multi-party talks while the IRA refused to agree to a
ceasefire.
</P>
<P>
"We would prefer to have Sinn Fein around the table rather than
not, but that is dependent on a meaningful ceasefire, an
unequivocal ceasefire with supporting words and deeds," Britain's
Northern Ireland Secretary Mo Mowlam told BBC radio.
</P>
<P>
The talks, which first started a year ago, were adjourned
during the British election, in which the Labor Party won a
landslide victory after 18 years in opposition.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein leader Adams said his party had a right to take part
in the talks which involve the province's other major parties.
</P>
<P>
"I am not going up to demand anything other than the rights of
those people who voted for us," said Adams, who was elected a
member of parliament in the May 1 election.
</P>
<P>
The Irish Republican Army has been fighting against British
rule in the Northern Ireland over the past 28 years through a
campaign of violence. It ended a 17-month ceasefire in February
1996 and resumed its military campaign.
</P>
<P>
Today's talks were chaired by former U.S. senator George
Mitchell, who seemed optimistic over the new round of negotiations.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that an opportunity exists to move forward in the
process and we hope very much that there will be substantive
progress in these talks in the near future," Mitchell said.
</P>
</TEXT>
