<HEADLINE> Chinese State Councilor Meets With Indian Broadcast Delegation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Li Tieying, a State Councilor and
Minister in charge of the State Commission for Restructuring the
Economy, meeting with a delegation from the Ministry of
Information and Broadcasting of India today, said that the Chinese
government supports cooperation between the Chinese and Indian
media.
</P>
<P>
Li told the delegation, which is led by Narottam Prasad Nawani,
state secretary to the Government of India, that radio, film and
television departments of the two countries have held frequent
exchanges and the Chinese government supports these exchanges
because they are beneficial to the promotion of good-neighborly
relations.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that both China and India have a very long
history and are two developing countries with the largest
populations, and have similar experiences in modern history and
face the same arduous tasks.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government places emphasis on strengthening
co-operative and good-neighborly relations with India and
encourages exchanges between the two countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope the media will reflect this fine
tradition of cooperation in the struggle against imperialism and
colonialism and the concerted efforts of the two countries to
safeguard world peace and stability on the basis of the five
principles of peaceful coexistence.
</P>
<P>
He said he believes that the promotion of good-neighborly
relations is not only in the interest of the two peoples, but also
a contribution to peace in Asia and the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
Nawani said that both countries have a long history and a huge
population and that visits between radio, film and television
sectors of the two countries have provided a solid foundation for
further cooperation, and that this will promote the development of
culture in the two countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
