<HEADLINE> PKK Kills 5 People in Southeastern Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Rebels of the outlawed Kurdish
Workers' Party (PKK) today killed five persons and wounded three
others in an attack on a village in southeastern Turkey, the
semi-official Anatolia News Agency said in a report today.
</P>
<P>
The report said that a group of PKK militants opened fire at
people who were digging a drinking water channel in Dikbogaz
village of the southeastern province of Siirt at about 12:00 local
time (09:00 GMT).
</P>
<P>
The Turkish security forces started large-scale operations to
capture the PKK rebels, but they escaped after the assault, said
the report.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, another group of PKK members set
two trucks on fire, which resulted in the deaths of the two
drivers of the vehicles in Siirt Province at midnight Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Khalil Attachi, leader of the PKK, was quoted by a newspaper as
saying that his group will attack Israeli and U.S. targets in
Turkish cities and tourist areas.
</P>
<P>
Attachi said that his group will "carry out operations against
Israeli targets in (Turkey's largest city) Istanbul and
elsewhere in Turkey and against U.S. enemy interests."
</P>
<P>
About 50,000-strong Turkish government troops have carried
out cross-border military operations in northern Iraq since
mid-May to attack the PKK.
</P>
<P>
Turkish military officials have said that more than 2,000 PKK
members have been killed in the military campaign in northern
Iraq, but the PKK claimed that its losses were less than 100
people.
</P>
<P>
The outlawed PKK has been fighting for autonomy in a almost
13-year-old separatist war in eastern and southeastern Turkey.
About 21,000 people, including civilians, government troops and
the PKK members have been killed so far. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
