<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Capital Reserves Surge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 3 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's gross gold and
foreign exchange reserves shot up 51 percent to 4.95 billion U.S.
dollars in May from 3.27 billion dollars at the end of April,
financial sources said today.
</P>
<P>
The surge in the reserves -- one month before the easing of
foreign exchange controls -- was bigger than even the most
optimistic forecasts, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
According to South Africa's Reserve Bank, the use of foreign
credit lines at the end of May was 409 million U.S. dollars against
568 million dollars in the previous month.
</P>
<P>
The figure means the markets will be relaxed ahead of the easing
of foreign exchange controls. It could also pave the way for
government to go a bit further than anticipated in the March budget
in easing controls, economic analysts said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
