<HEADLINE> Jospin Meets Communist Leader on Forming Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 3 (Xinhua) -- France's new Socialist Prime Minister
Lionel Jospin today held talks with Communist Party leader Robert
Hue over his party's participation in the new government.
</P>
<P>
No details were disclosed about their one-hour meeting, but
both Socialist and Communist officials expressed optimism about a
deal.
</P>
<P>
The Communists, who won 38 seats in the new French parliament
in Sunday's election, have presented a set of socio-economic
proposals for the new government, including a 500-franc (80
U.S. dollars) increase in the guaranteed minimum wage, a reduction
of the 20.6 percent sales tax, and an aid program for small and
medium-sized businesses.
</P>
<P>
Jospin, appointed Monday by center-right President Jacques
Chirac, discussed with Hue the policy "content" of the new
government and its make-up, Agence France-Presse quoted sources as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The Socialist Party won 252 seats in the 557-seat parliament in
Sunday's general election and will have to ally with the Communist
Party and smaller left parties to form a government and gain an
absolute majority.
</P>
<P>
The Communist Party's decision-making national council Monday
adopted a resolution agreeing to join the government if an
agreement is reached with the Socialists.
</P>
<P>
The resolution was discussed on Monday night by local Communist
Party organizations and will be re-examined by the national
council and grassroots party organizations today.
</P>
<P>
Party officials said that the Communists will not enter the
government "with an empty hand" and must force the Socialists to
make some commitments.
</P>
<P>
The last time the Communist Party joined a government was in
1981, when President Francois Mitterrand had four Communist
ministers in his Socialist government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
