<DOCNO> XIE19970603.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Airlines Continues to Lose Money </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Airlines (PAL), which
has been in the red for years, said today that it registered
losses amounting to 1.4 billion pesos (53.4 million U.S. dollars)
during the first quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
In a disclosure to the Securities and Exchange Commission, the
PAL said the losses were a further deterioration from the previous
quarter's net loss of 1.2 billion pesos (45.8 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
However, the PAL reported that its revenues increased by 594.9
million pesos (22.7 million dollars) while operating expenses rose
by a higher amount of 726.8 million pesos (27.7 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
"The increase in operating expenses was mainly due to higher
flying operations expenses, passenger service expenses and lease
charges," the disclosure said.
</P>
<P>
Lucio Tan, a Filipino-Chinese tycoon who owns over 56 percent
of the PAL, predicted earlier that the carrier will incur 2
billion to 3 billion pesos' losses this year and continue to be
loss-making until 1999.
</P>
<P>
According to Tan, the PAL will begin to make profit in 1999
when the company gradually implements its 4-billion-dollar
modernization program.  
</P>
</TEXT>
