<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-03 14:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Syria: Mideast Peace Process Is Dead </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARIO, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Syrian Foreign Minister Farouk
al-Shara has voiced his frustration with the peace process which
he said is dead because of insincerity on the Israeli side.
</P>
<P>
"At present there is literally no such thing as a Mideast peace
process," Shara said in an Egyptian TV program aired today.
</P>
<P>
He said in the interview that the Israeli government does not
seem serious in re-starting the peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
"Syria believes that the peace process must be regarded as a
whole package," he said, "It must be understood that no success
can be reached on one track while the other tracks are left in
failure."
</P>
<P>
Peace negotiations between Israel and Syria started in 1991 but
were frozen since last February after a spate of suicide bombings
in Israel blamed on Palestinian extremists.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the Palestinian-Israeli talks have plunged
into crisis since March when Israel broke ground for a new Jewish
settlement in the disputed Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Syria has demanded a pan-Arab summit to make resolute decisions
to confront Israel's hardline policies and boycott any regional and
multilateral cooperation that involves the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
"Though the Arabs' peace talks with Israel take the bilateral
shape, none of the Arab negotiating parties nor any of the Arab
countries would ever accept anything short of a comprehensive
peace," Shara told the Egyptian TV.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the tension in the area to the failure to
establish a just and all-out peace based on international
legitimacy and the principle of trading land for peace.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian foreign minister criticized Israel for demanding to
start talks with the Syrians from scratch.
</P>
<P>
"Syria insists that Syrian and Israeli negotiators pick up from
where they left off," he said. "Its stand is unanimously backed by
the Arab and world communities and the co-sponsors of the peace
march," he said.
</P>
<P>
It is impossible to strike out five years of negotiations and
forget about all achieved steps, he said.
</P>
<P>
He warned that Israel's refusal to commit itself to its
previous obligations would give the opportunity to others to
follow its example in the future.
</P>
<P>
"This would be very serious because it would mean that any
party can go back on its commitments at any time in the future,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Syria said it will not return to the negotiating table with the
Israelis unless they first agree to pull out of the Golan Heights,
captured by the Jewish state in 1967.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu rejects the demand,
saying that the strategic plateau is vital to Israel. But his
predecessors, Labor Party leaders reportedly verbally accepted an
Israeli withdrawal from the Golan in return for normalized ties
with Syria.
</P>
<P>
Syrian Vice President Abdul-Halim Khaddam and al-Shara arrived
here Monday morning on a lightning visit to hold talks with
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, the first country to make peace with the Jewish state,
has been one of the key mediators in the peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
