<HEADLINE> Mongolia Cracks Down on Corruption in Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Mongolia's National Supervisory
Committee (NSCM) recovered illegally-obtained property worth 670
million Tugrik (about 845,000 U.S. dollars) in the first quarter
of this year, the national newspaper People's Right reported here
today.
</P>
<P>
Strengthening the supervision of funds in state bodies and
state-owned enterprises, the NSCM and its provincial branches
investigated more than 160 units, discovering a serious drain on
state-owned assets and embezzlement of public funds.
</P>
<P>
Among 1,500 cadres investigated, 39 were arrested on charges of
committing serious financial crimes and illegally obtaining 37.7
million Tugrik (about 47,000 dollars).
</P>
<P>
Fines of 1.2 million Tugrik (about 1,500 dollars) were imposed
on another 60 people. Disciplinary measures were taken against
more than 40 people.
</P>
<P>
Banzragch, the secretary general of the NSCM, was quoted as
saying that the amount of "dirty" money recovered in the first
three months of this year was five times more than that in the
same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
The number of people who received administrative and
disciplinary punishment was double that of the same period last
year, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
