<HEADLINE> Cyprus Protests Turkish Violations of Air Space </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The Cypriot government will protest
to the United Nations and other international fora against new
Turkish violations of Cyprus' air space, Government Spokesman
Manolis Christofides said here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at his daily press briefing, Christofides revealed
that three Turkish F4-fighters intruded into Cyprus' air space
today.
</P>
<P>
"Turkey has opted to go down the road of provocative moves and
violation of international law and order," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated the government's resolve "to stick to an earlier
decision on a halt of overflights of Greek military aircraft over
Cyprus ahead of direct talks between the Greek and Turkish Cypriot
sides."
</P>
<P>
This decision, he pointed out, "is part of our established
policy to show good will and create the right atmosphere for
these talks, expected to take place in New York in early July."
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has sponsored proximity talks between the Greek and
Turkish Cypriot sides for the past two months in an effort to
create the right atmosphere for the U.N.-proposed direct talks
between leaders of the two communities on the island.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan will soon issue invitations
to the two community's leaders for face-to-face negotiations in
searching for a comprehensive solution to the protracted problem
of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The local press reported earlier that two Turkish patrol boats
violated Monday night Cyprus' territorial waters, off the island's
southeastern coast.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that that violation, and today's illegal air
activity are "part of Turkey's continuous provocative action."
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus problem has remained unsolved since 1974 when the
island was divided after the Turkish troops invaded and took
control of its northern third in the wake of a short-lived coup
seeking union with Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
