<HEADLINE> Chinese Seminar on Book of Changes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 3 (Xinhua) -- A seminar on "The Book of Changes
and Fortune-telling" held by the China Association for Science and
Technology opened in Beijing today to discuss a 3,000-year-old
Chinese philosophy classic.
</P>
<P>
Attending were sociologists, psychologists, religious study
people, historians, and experts on the Book of Changes, with Gong
Yuzhi, vice-president of the Party School of the Communist Party
of China Central Committee, chairing the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The classic work and its status in Chinese culture is still a
controversial issue in Chinese academies.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Bokun, a Philosophy Department professor at Beijing
University and an expert on the work, said that some people have
confused the study of the Book of Changes with fortune telling by
saying that fortune telling is the main function of the
book. "This viewpoint has caused great confusion in the
development of traditional culture and it must be clarified," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Participants pointed out that fortune telling is the product of
the age of barbarism and can not withstand scientific scrutiny,
and that, in studying the Book of Changes, what should be
maintained is its good tradition, especially its dialectical mode
of thinking. They asked the government to halt superstitious
activities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
