<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 95th Anniversary of "Ta Kung Pao" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 3 (Xinhua) -- An exhibition to mark the 95th
anniversary of the founding of the Hong Kong-based Chinese
language newspaper "Ta Kung Pao" opened here today.
</P>
<P>
On display were some 120 pages of the paper on historic events,
including a report of the May 4th Movement, the September 18th
Incident, the July 7th Incident, and events from around the world
over the past 50 years.
</P>
<P>
Chinese leaders Jiang Zemin, Li Peng, Qiao Shi, Li Ruihuan and
Liu Huaqing wrote congratulatory messages. Jiang wrote: "Carry
forward the tradition of love of country and Hong Kong, and
implement the one country, two systems principle to the letter."
</P>
<P>
Li wrote: "Spread the elegance of China, and maintain the
prosperity of Hong Kong," while Qiao wrote: "Carry forward the
fine traditions and make new contributions to the stability and
prosperity of Hong Kong and the peaceful reunification of the
motherland."
</P>
<P>
Li Ruihuan wrote: "Be confident and just." Liu Huaqing
wrote: "Love the country and people, and invigorate the Chinese
nation."
</P>
<P>
"Ta Kung Pao" was started in 1902 in Tianjin and is the oldest
Chinese language newspaper in the world. It has lived through many
historical periods, such as the late Qing Dynasty, the 1911
Revolution, the Great Revolution, the War of Resistance Against
Japanese Aggression, and the War of Liberation, and has had to
change its address to Hankou, Shanghai, Hong Kong, Chongqing, and
Guilin.
</P>
<P>
Attending today's ceremony were Cheng Siyuan, vice-chairman of
the Standing Committee of the National People's Congress; Zeng
Jianhui, director of the Information Office of the State Council;
and Liu Mingqi, vice-director of the Hong Kong and Macao Affairs
Office of the State Council. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
