<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Adopts New Disaster Prevention Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Japan today adopted a new disaster
prevention program designed to have a quick response to any major
accidents and natural calamities in the future.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese government was widely criticized for its slow
response to pleas for help from local governments following the
Hanshin earthquake on January 17, 1995, which killed more
than 6,000 people.
</P>
<P>
Under the new program, which was revised in July 1995 after the
Hanshin earthquake, the supply of running water will be curbed in
the case of a nuclear power accident and a special task force will
be set up to fight oil spills at sea, Kyodo News reported.
</P>
<P>
The measures outlined in the program represent Japan's first
package of steps to deal with accidents in eight areas -- sea,
aviation, railway, highway, nuclear power, dangerous materials,
large fires and forest fires.
</P>
<P>
The program was adopted at a meeting attended by Prime Minister
Ryutaro Hashimoto and his cabinet, the heads of the Bank of Japan,
the Japanese Red Cross and Nippon Telegraph and Telephone Corp..
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto told the meeting that disaster prevention is one of
his government's key objectives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
