<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Repairing House of Qing Dynasty Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Work to repair the former residence
of Lin Zexu, a national hero known for burning opium during the
Qing Dynasty (1644-1911), began today in Fuzhou, the capital of
Fujian Province in east China.
</P>
<P>
In 1839, Lin started a ban on smuggling and abusing opium,
triggering the outbreak of the First Opium War between China and
Britain. The war is regarded by many Chinese historians as marking
the beginning of modern Chinese history.
</P>
<P>
The 3,000-sq-m residence is located on the Wenzao Hill near
West Lake in Fuzhou. It contains many works of Xu's calligraphy,
and of his family members, and the emperor of that time, Daoguang.
</P>
<P>
The residence was badly damaged by floods in 1948. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
