<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading U.S. newspapers published today:
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Timothy McVeigh was convicted Monday of the worst act of
domestic terrorism in American history, the bombing of the Alfred
Murrah Federal Building in Oklahoma City that killed 168.
</P>
<P>
-- Canadian Prime Minister Jean Chretien's Liberal Party won
the national legislative elections by a slim margin late Monday.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- French President Jacques Chirac Monday appointed Socialist
leader Lionel Jospin as the new prime minister. Jospin is to take
office Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
-- Ships, planes and troops from Nigeria and other West African
nations sought to subdue a military coup in Sierra Leone, where
they encountered heavy resistance.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- U.S. Republicans prepared legislation to trim about 115
billion U.S. dollars from Medicare plan over five years while
providing new benefits and health-plan choices.
</P>
<P>
-- British Prime Minister Tony Blair Monday expressed regret
for London's policies during Ireland's potato famine of the 1840s,
which killed at least one million people and forced another two
million to emigrate. 
</P>
