<HEADLINE> Roundup: Foreign Investors Bullish over HK's Future(1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Recent surveys show that Hong
Kong is still "the best place to do business" in the eyes of
foreign investors, with most of them choosing to expand investment
or continue business as usual after the handover.
</P>
<P>
A latest survey conducted by the British Chamber of Commerce in
Hong Kong showed that 93 percent of British companies will be
operating here in the year 2000 and 70 percent will expand
business. Only 7 percent said they are unsure.
</P>
<P>
Most British companies believed that after the handover the
business climate will remain unchanged, and in certain aspects --
such as access to the Chinese mainland and trade links between
China and Britain -- will even improve, according to the chairman
of the chamber, Patrick Paul.
</P>
<P>
Britain is currently the largest investor in Hong Kong with an
accumulated investment of 40 billion U.S. dollars, followed by
Japan with 14.3 billion U.S. dollars and the United States with 12
billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
British Senior Trade Commissioner in Hong Kong Francis Cornish
said that Hong Kong, after the handover, will be a place full of
opportunities, with the complement of buoyant stock and property
markets, recovered retail sales and improved employment, in
addition to an easy access to the huge market of inland areas.
</P>
<P>
Like their British counterparts, American companies have also
been playing an active role in the town. To them, Hong Kong's
return to China is definitely not an interruption.
</P>
<P>
According to Frank Martin, president of the American Chamber of
 Commerce (AmCham) in Hong Kong, American companies will increase
investment year by year both in Hong Kong and on the Chines inland
areas.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on some Western media reports depicting a gloomy
picture of post-handover Hong Kong, Martin stressed that their
effect on the business sector, if there is any, is very limited.
</P>
<P>
He predicted that results of this year's AmCham confidence
survey, to be published in October, will be similar to those of
last year, that is, some 95 percent of AmCham member companies
will continue their investment in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The 1996 AmCham business confidence survey showed that a record
high of 95 percent consider Hong Kong's business environment up to
2001 as "very favorable" or "favorable".
</P>
<P>
In the next three years, 53 percent plan to expand business and
42 percent will continue "business as usual". Among the 457
companies that maintain regional headquarters in Hong Kong, 46
percent will expand.
</P>
<P>
AmCham is the largest U.S. chamber of commerce outside the
United States, grouping some 1,100 American companies. It has
conducted the annual confidence survey since 1990.
</P>
<P>
Japan's Consul General in Hong Kong, Hideaki Ueda, said that
Hong Kong's handover to China is a great event either to the
Asia-Pacific region or to the whole world and that Japan's
confidence in Hong Kong is manifest with the rapidly growing
economic and trade linkage between the two economies.
</P>
<P>
Out of a total of 182 licensed banks operating in Hong Kong, 43
are Japanese-funded with their combined capital accounting for 45
percent of all the banks here put together.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
