<HEADLINE> Pak Concerned over Deployment of Missiles by India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan today expressed its
"serious concern" over India's deployment of medium-range
ballistic Prithvi missiles near Pakistan's borders, saying it
reserved its right to take necessary measures for its security.
</P>
<P>
"The deployment of Prithvi missiles entails a qualitative
change in the security environment in South Asia and could trigger
a dangerous ballistic arms race in the region," said a Foreign
Office official here today.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan had made a proposal for a zero missile zone regime in
South Asia, said the official, adding that it "reserves the right
to take necessary measures to safeguard its security".
</P>
<P>
Pakistan had in the past also drawn the attention of the
international community to India's intentions of deploying this
missile which can carry weapons of mass destruction, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Asia Business News, a Honk Kong-based TV, reported today
that the missiles have reportedly been moved to a location near
the city of Jullundur in the state of Punjab in Northwest India.
This is the first operational deployment of the missile, it added.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
