<DOCNO> XIE19970603.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Agency Calls for Greenhouse Gas Curbs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Japan's Environmental Agency today
criticized the government for failing to do enough to curb carbon
dioxide emissions and other gases blamed for causing global
warming.
</P>
<P>
The agency also called for legislation to regulate greenhouse
gas emissions and set up an environment tax.
</P>
<P>
It said the government's energy policy should shift its
priority away from securing a stable supply of energy to cutting
carbon dioxide emissions.
</P>
<P>
In its 1997 annual report, the agency called on the government
to draft legislation to set out fuel efficiency standards for
vehicles, impose taxes on carbon dioxide emissions and promote
garbage-fuel generators so as to prevent further global warming.
</P>
<P>
The agency also called on Japanese people to adopt a more
environmentally friendly lifestyle, even if it caused
inconvenience, for the sake of future generations and the Earth's
environment.
</P>
<P>
The appeal came against the background of an 8.3 percent
increase in carbon dioxide emissions in Japan in fiscal 1995 over
the previous year, casting doubt on whether Japan can meet a
non-binding target for keeping greenhouse gas emissions at 1990
levels by 2000 set by the U.N. Framework Convention on Climate
Change.
</P>
<P>
Japan will host a third conference of the signatory nations to
the climate change convention, which was first signed at the Rio
De Janeiro Earth summit in Brazil in 1992 and came into force in
1994.
</P>
<P>
The conference is to be held in the western city of Kyoto in
December, bringing together more than 150 signatory states to
adopt a protocol on a legally binding reduction in carbon dioxide
emissions after 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970603.0118 </DOCNO>
