<DOCNO> XIE19970603.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Foreign Investors Bullish Over HK's Future(2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
According to the HK Industry Department's 1996 survey of
external investment in Hong Kong's manufacturing industries,
Japanese investment topped the list with roughly 40 percent of the
total.
</P>
<P>
An international school was set up earlier this year for
children of an increasing number of Japanese nationals working
here.
</P>
<P>
Apart from Britain, the U.S. and Japan, the European Union,
Australia and Asian countries also cast a vote of confidence for
Hong Kong, expecting Hong Kong to preserve all the factors
contributing to her past miracle.
</P>
<P>
For French companies, the 1997 factor has positively affected
their investment strategy, with 90 percent planning to expand
business here, according to a latest survey by the French Business
Association in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Australia's Consul General in Hong Kong Geoff Walsh believed
that the territory has been, and will continue to be, a window for
China, thanks to its advanced financial services, transportation
and communications facilities.
</P>
<P>
Businessmen from India, Malaysia, South Africa and other
countries also chose to maintain their presence here in the belief
that the handover will bring them more opportunities.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics showed that the number of foreign companies
operating in Hong Kong has been on the rise steadily. Of the 4,500
foreign companies operating here, about 40 percent rushed in
within the past five years. And this year will probably see an 8
percent increase over last year in the number of foreign companies
setting up regional headquarters or offices here.
</P>
<P>
Foreign companies have every reason to put their money in the
city, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
In the transitional year, Hong Kong beat over 100 rivals,
including Singapore and the United States, to be the freest
economy around the globe. It is the fourth consecutive time that
Hong Kong won the title in an international survey on economic
freedom.
</P>
<P>
U.S. credit rating agency Standard &AMP; Poor's also underlined its
confidence in post-handover Hong Kong by lifting its ratings on
Hong Kong and China.
</P>
<P>
Several days later, a report entitled World Economic Outlook,
published by the International Monetary Fund, upgraded Hong Kong
from a developing economic entity to an advanced economic entity,
in a signal to recognize the city's sophisticated financial
services, economic diversity and growing integration with the
vibrant economy on the Chinese mainland.
</P>
<P>
And there are also persuasive figures. At the end of May, the
Hong Kong government announced that Hong Kong's economic growth
bounced back to 6 percent in the first quarter of this year, the
highest for a period of two years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
