<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Should Increase Humanities Exchanges with Foreign Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Increasing exchanges with
international academic circles will help China keep abreast of new
developments of theories and ideas in the fields of humanities and
social sciences, Ru Xin, vice president of the Chinese Academy of
Social Sciences (CASS), said here today.
</P>
<P>
Ru was speaking at a ceremony to confer the title of honorary
academy member of the CASS upon three foreign scholars. The
academy has given the title to 13 foreigners since December.
</P>
<P>
Experts said that this indicates the CASS is set to open wider
to the rest of the world, in light of close international
cooperation in science and technology.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Academy of Sciences gave the title of academician
to the first group of foreigners on June 3 of last year. Some
experts suggested that more efforts be made in humanities.
</P>
<P>
The CASS's honors were given today to Jozef Titzen, the Dutch
minister of Education, Culture and Science, Sumiya Mikio, director
of the Social Science Department of the Japanese Academy of
Science, and James Matisoff, professor of University of California
at Berkeley in the United States.
</P>
<P>
Ru said that the conferment of the title demonstrates the
CASS's commendation and recognition of the foreign scholars'
outstanding contributions in the fields of humanities and social
sciences. 
</P>
</TEXT>
