<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Concerned Over Situation in Cambodia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Foreign Minister
Abdullah Ahmad Badawi said today the Association of Southeast
Asian Nations (ASEAN) is concerned over what's happening in
Cambodia, fearing that it may affect the region's stability.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah, who is also ASEAN Standing Committee chairman,
expressed the hope that the disputing parties in Cambodia will
sort out their differences in the interest of the country's peace
and stability.
</P>
<P>
"What's happening in Cambodia is an internal matter... we
cannot intervene in domestic matters. Nevertheless, ASEAN is
concerned over what's happening as we fear it may affect the
region's stability," he told reporters here.
</P>
<P>
The remarks came after political tension flared up within the
Cambodian government.
</P>
<P>
Cambodia along with Myanmar and Laos will be formally admitted
into the ASEAN in July this year as decided by ASEAN foreign
ministers at their one-day special meeting here on May 31.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN now groups Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, Singapore, the
Philippines, Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN countries could still advise feuding leaders in that
country to resolve their differences, Abdullah added.
</P>
<P>
He said Malaysia is adopting an advisory approach as it has
substantial investments in Cambodia, believing Cambodian leaders
will understand Malaysia's approach as it will be wise of them to
bury the hatchet.
</P>
<P>
The minister also advised Malaysian investors in Cambodia to
monitor the developments to assess whether they want to invest
there or otherwise.  
</P>
</TEXT>
