<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Sees Growth of Consumer Goods Exports to Taiwan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's exports of consumer
goods to Taiwan have experienced phenomenal growth since 1990 in
tandem with the opening of Taiwan's import market, according to a
market report released today by the Hong Kong Trade Development
Council (TDC).
</P>
<P>
The report said the most remarkable growth was seen in
footwear, followed by apparel, jewelry and toys.
</P>
<P>
Market penetration of Hong Kong's consumer goods is high,
especially of those products for which Hong Kong suppliers have
established a strong presence in Taiwan. The import market share
of T-shirts, singlets and other goods from Hong Kong was about 50
percent, and that of jewelry was 37 percent in 1995, according to
the report.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1980s, Taiwan has gradually opened up its consumer
market to imports and overseas participation. After several rounds
of tariff cuts, the average nominal import tariff rate has been
reduced from over 20 percent to the present 6.52 percent. As a
result, imports grew at an average annual rate of 15.4 percent
between 1986 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
The report said that both Hong Kong and Japanese groups are now
major players in Taiwan's retail sector. However, as the market is
set to become increasingly competitive, Hong Kong suppliers should
further enhance their strengths in order to stay ahead of the
pack, it said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
