<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Likely to Resort to Imports to Fight Fuel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The Nigieran government is likely to once
again adopt the emergency measure of fuel importation for an immediate
solution to the persistent scarcity in the country.
</P>
<P>
The latest round of fuel crisis in the leading African oil
producing country has lasted for about two weeks, reducing commercial
activities especially in the nation's economic nerve center of Lagos
where transporters have hiked fares by about 200 percent.
</P>
<P>
As respite from the fuel scarcity still looks remote, officials of
the Nigerian National Petroleum Corporation (NNPC) and the Ministry of
Petroleum Resources might soon meet with Presidency officials on the
matter, the Vanguard reported today.
</P>
<P>
The local daily quoted a highly-placed source close to the ministry
as attributing the fuel crisis to the inadequate of government
allocation of crude oil to the nation's four refineries.
</P>
<P>
According to a government policy, crude oil produced for domestic
consumption this year should be 250,000 barrels per day compared to
the usual 500,000 barrels in order to avoid wastages and have budget
surplus.
</P>
<P>
"As at today there are no reserve stocks at the various
refineries," the source said, adding that the present situation was
bound to worsen by the time Kaduna Refinery in northern Nigeria begins
turn around maintenance next month.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the best thing for the government to do is to
import fuels, which the NNPC has been advocating since the beginning
of the year.
</P>
<P>
The NNPC is responsible for overseeing the country's production and
supply of crude oil and related commodities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
