<DOCNO> XIE19970603.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulletin Shows Good Environment in Three Gorges Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The latest environmental monitoring
bulletin reports that the Three Gorges reservoir area along the
middle reaches of the Yangtze River is maintaining an acceptable
ecological balance.
</P>
<P>
According to the bulletin released today by the Three Gorges
Construction Commission under the State Council and the State
Bureau of Environmental Protection, the Three Gorges project did
not have direct impact on the area's natural ecology, local
economy, and resettlement of residents in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The construction did destroy previous vegetation and caused
soil losses to some extent. But with accelerating restoration
efforts, the vegetation will soon improve, the bulletin says.
</P>
<P>
The bulletin indicates that practical technology for enhancing
ecological agriculture, public health promotion mechanisms, and
environmental protection measures, in the construction areas have
played an important role in maintaining good local ecological
conditions.
</P>
<P>
To further step up efforts of environmental protection, the
commission and the bureau announced today that comprehensive
ecological and environmental monitorings in the Three Gorges area
had begun.
</P>
<P>
The monitoring network will cover resettlement, quality of
water, pollution sources, hydrology, regional climate, mountain
disasters, fish and aquatic creatures, land animals and plants,
health of people, agricultural ecology, and social environment.
</P>
<P>
Monitoring will be carried out along the entire process of
project, and bulletins will be publicized on a regular basis,
officials said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
