<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Up Amid Rate Concerns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar ended today
on a slightly firmer note amid speculation over a possible easing
of official interest rates in the short term while bond prices
also closed higher.
</P>
<P>
The Reserve Bank of Australia held its monthly board meeting
today and some players suggested the central bank could ease
policy as early as tomorrow morning.
</P>
<P>
However, other analysts believed this was unlikely as it would
be so close to the last rate cut on May 23 when the bank lowered
the official cash rate to 5.5 percent from 6.0 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar ended at 75.96 US cents, up from 75.85 at
the previous local close.
</P>
<P>
Offshore last night the Australian dollar traded to a high of
76.08 US cents during the London session and fell to as low as
75.66 in New York.
</P>
<P>
On the cross-rates, the Australian dollar ended stronger. It
was at 88.21 from 88.13 against the Japanese yen, and at 1.3127
from 1.2992 against German mark.  
</P>
