<HEADLINE> Jordan, U.S. Pledge Stronger Military Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian and U.S. officials agreed
to strengthen bilateral military ties at a meeting here today as a
major military exercise between the two countries is going on in
the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Regional situation is also among the topics of the meeting
between Chairman of the Jordanian Joint Chief of Staff Field
Marshal Abdul Hafez Marei Kaabneh and Commander Jefferson Hawl
from the U.S. Central Command which is in charge of the U.S.
overseas military operations, Radio Jordan reported.
</P>
<P>
The current 4-week long war game is code-named "Infinite
Moonlight '97" and due to end on June 19. The latest round was
conducted Saturday in the desert 80 kilometers south of Amman,
rallying about 2,500 soldiers and featuring helicopters, jet
fighters as well as heavy and light weapons.
</P>
<P>
The war game is part of the military coordination between
Jordan and the U.S., which granted the former the title of
non-North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) ally last year to
make Jordan legible for military assistance.
</P>
<P>
Last December, Jordan received a 100 million U.S. dollars
military aid from the U.S. as part of a total of 300 million
dollars assistance pledged by the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
The U.S., who bears important economic interests in the Middle
East, also maintains close military relationship with Israel and
Turkey in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
