<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Down on Profit-Taking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market ended
weaker today on profit-taking following today's first Reserve Bank
meeting since a recent interest rate cut.
</P>
<P>
The All Ordinaries index slid 12.1 points to 2613.6, with most
sectors seeing declines throughout the day.
</P>
<P>
Brokers said there was plenty of profit-taking after the
bullish run here last week and yesterday, when the All Ordinaries
reached a record closing high of 2625.7.
</P>
<P>
"I think there was a bit of profit-taking," Reynolds and Co.
dealer Markus Mueller said.
</P>
<P>
Mueller also said that following the recent interest rate cut,
there was uncertainty about where the economy was placed.
</P>
<P>
The All Industrials index slipped 11 points to 4078.4 while the
banking index finished 24.2 points lower at 4580.4.
</P>
<P>
The All Resources index closed 14.2 points down at 1488.7, with
the stock of the resource giant, BHP, down 28 cents and WMC 15.3
cents.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 380.05 million shares valued at 1.09
billion Australian dollars (826 million U.S. dollars).  
</P>
</TEXT>
