<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items in
leading French newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- The Socialist leader Lionel Jospin, who will form his
government within one week, is faced with of hot issues such as
the revision of the budget, freezing the privatization of state
enterprises, the dispute over Renault automaker's closing down of
its Vilvoorde plant in Belgium and a record high unemployment rate.
</P>
<P>
-- The German government, which is facing a serious budgetary
problem to attain the criteria set by the Maastricht treaty to
qualify for the European single currency, is worried about the
conditions presented by the new French Prime Minister Lionel
Jospin for the launching of the Euro.
</P>
<P>
Jospin has called for a flexible interpretation of the
Maastricht treaty, the admission of Italy and Spain into the
monetary union in the first wave, and the inclusion in the
Maastricht treaty of a pact on employment rather than a pact of
stability Bonn wanted.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- Prime Minister Alain Juppe today formally handed over the
prime minister's seat to Socialist Party first secretary Lionel
Jospin.
</P>
<P>
The Socialist Party leaders held a closed-door meeting Monday
at the residence of Jospin to discuss the forming of the
government. The Communist Party presented its proposals on
economic and social policies for the new government and was
waiting for a "concrete response" from Jospin before accepting to
enter the new government.
</P>
<P>
-- The victory of the French left in the legislative election
and the nomination of Lionel Jospin as prime minister were well
received by the French financial market. The Paris Bourse closed
Monday with a 0.68 percent rise of its CAC 40 index, while the
French franc stayed firm in exchange rate with the German mark.
</P>
</TEXT>
