</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Progress has been made in the negotiations on
Egypt-European Union (EU) partnership, with the two sides having
agreed on almost 90 percent of the agreement's clauses, Egypt's
Ambassador to Belgium and the EU Mohamed Shaaban said today.
</P>
<P>
After nine rounds of negotiations since January 1995, Egypt and
the EU are finally edging near a partnership, Shaaban told the
Cairo-based Voice of Arab radio in an interview.
</P>
<P>
But he did not specify where lies the other 10 percent of the
difference, which might be vital for clinching the deal.
</P>
<P>
Egypt accused the EU of imposing interests at its expense by
giving European manufactures free access to the Egyptian markets
but keeping quotas on exports of Egyptian food.
</P>
<P>
Europe, which receives 47 percent of Egyptian exports, is
Egypt's major trading partner, according to Shaaban.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador said Egypt's political weight in the region also
avails a speedy conclusion of the economic association accord
which will provide for establishing a free trade zone between them
by the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
Shaaban called on the industrial sector to prepare itself before
the signing of the Egypt-EU Partnership Agreement, to improve the
quality of the Egyptian product and to protect it in the European
market.
</P>
<P>
Egypt still fears that its own products, which are relatively
inferior in quality and price, are blocked from reaching the EU
markets.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Federal Express (FedEx), the world's largest
express transport company, has begun regular flights between the
U.S. and Tel Aviv, reported The Jerusalem Post Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
FedEx uses its own Boeing 727 all-cargo aircraft to fly to and
from Israel four times a week.
</P>
<P>
David Bronczek, the company's senior vice president for Europe,
the Middle East and Africa, noted Monday that the decision to
upgrade service to Israel comes as a result of the international
business company's interest in the growing economy in Israel.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel's exports of polished diamonds for the
January-May period this year totaled 1.82 billion U.S. dollars,
an 8 percent increase over the same period last year, reported The
Jerusalem Post Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Polished-diamond exports rose 14.5 percent last month to 405
million dollars from 354 million in May last year.
</P>
<P>
Exports of unpolished diamonds rose 42 percent last month to 73
million from 51 million in May last year.
</P>
<P>
For the January-May period, exports of raw diamonds rose to
430 million from 288 million in the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
In the January-May period, 47 percent of the exports were to
the U.S., 19 percent were to Hong Kong, 14 percent to Japan and 12
percent to Belgium.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Turkey will soon begin implementing the free-trade
agreement with Israel, reported local newspapers, quoting Turkish
Ambassador Barlas Ozener as saying.
</P>
<P>
Although bureaucratic delays made Turkey not able to adhere to
the original May 1 implementation date, Ozener said the deal is
currently circulating among the 40 ministers who have to sign it,
and he hopes free trade will begin "within the next few days."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, both sides are requiring importers to sign bank
guarantees in case the deal does not get passed.
</P>
<P>
The agreement is designed to increase trade between the two
countries. Bilateral trade totaled 500 million U.S. dollars in
1995.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordan has instructed all its embassies around the
world to offer investment and economic services to foreign
businessmen soon to help the country's economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
All the embassies are also obliged to provide the necessary
facilities to foreign private sector delegations coming to Jordan,
said Foreign Minister Fayez Tarawneh quoted in local press today.
</P>
<P>
The embassies are especially urged to provide services such as
hotel reservations, hiring cars, hosting receptions, fixing
appointments for delegations and establishing a follow-up
mechanism on a case-by-case basis, the minister told a meeting
with the representatives of trade and industry chambers here
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Major recovering steps by Jordan include drawing foreign
investment, establishing the Aqaba free trade zone and further
developing sectoral economy such as tourism, phosphate production
and pharmacy.
</P>
<P>
Before the Gulf crisis (1990-1991), Jordan, although scant of
natural resources, had a flourishing economy thanks to a great
amount of aid from various resources.
</P>
<P>
But most aid from other Arab states and the West were stopped
because Jordan sided with Iraq who invaded Kuwait after the war,
making the economy going down. By the end of 1996, its foreign
debt equaled to 90 percent of its gross national product.
</P>
</TEXT>
