<HEADLINE> 65 Dead From Nigeria's Intervention in S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, June 3 (Xinhua) - - Sixtyfive People, mainly
civilians, have died in Monday's bombardment by Nigerian forces
as they tried to reverse the coup in Sierra Leone which toppled
the civilian government about eight days ago.
</P>
<P>
Most of the dead had their limbs and faces mutilated and
hundreds are said to have been injured.
</P>
<P>
The capital remained calm and Nigerian troops have now
retreated to a base at Jui, about 15 miles from the capital.
Eyewitnesses said the base is now surrounded by Sierra Leonean
troops.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, a truce brokered by the International Committee of
the Red Cross (ICRC) freed over 1,000 people including foreign
journalists who were trapped in fighting after the seaside hotel
was partially destroyed.
</P>
<P>
The Sierra Leonean army is holding a number of Nigerian
soldiers. The S.Leonean military government has given an
ultimatum for all Nigerian troops to leave Sierra Leone by
Tuesday, warning that the order ''will be rigorously enforced.''
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic sources in Freetown said that the British
ambassador, Peter Penford and his deputy have been asked by the
Foreign Office in London to proceed to neighbouring Guinea
''until tension subsides". 
</P>
</TEXT>
