<HEADLINE> Splinter Group of Ethnic Party Surrenders in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, June 3 (Xinhua) -- One hundred and fifty members of a
breakaway group of the New Mon State Party (NMSP), a former
anti-government ethnic armed group in Myanmar, have surrendered to
the government last weekend.
</P>
<P>
Official sources said today that the splinter group of the NMSP
-- the Beik Mon Army (BMA) led by its battalion commander Aung
Thaik Hym -- "traded their arms for peace" on May 31 in the Beik
area of Mon State, turning in 470 assorted weapons.
</P>
<P>
The BMA broke away from the NMSP led by Naing Shwe Kyin in
November 1996 after the NMSP returned to the legal fold in June
1995 due to inter-party differences, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
More BMA members, stationed across the border, are expected to
follow suit, the sources added.
</P>
<P>
Altogether 16 ethnic armed groups as well as former drug
warlord Khun Sa's Mong Tai Army (MTA) have returned to the legal
fold in Myanmar, leaving the only largest one -- the Kayin
National Union -- still in operation on the Myanmar-Thai border.
</P>
</TEXT>
