<HEADLINE> 85th International Labor Conference Opens in Geneva </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, May 29 (Xinhua) -- About 3,000 delegates from the 174
member states of the International Labor Organization (ILO) met
here today to attend the 85th International Labor Conference from
June 3-19.
</P>
<P>
The delegates will try to promote universal respect for core
labor standards, harness the employment-generating potential of
small and medium-sized enterprises, modernize the regime governing
fee-charging employment agencies and adopt the ILO's program and
budget for 1998-99, according to an ILO press release.
</P>
<P>
King Hussein of Jordan, guest of honor of the 1997 conference,
will address a special plenary session on June 13.
</P>
<P>
James Wolfensohn, the president of the World Bank, is also
scheduled to address a plenary session on June 12.
</P>
<P>
He will participate in an informal discussion on "Social
progress: Common concerns and strategies in a globalizing world"
to be held at the ILO headquaters with labor ministers and
delegates representing employers and workers.
</P>
<P>
China's Labor Minister Li Boyong will address the plenary on
June 10. A Chinese delegation consisting of representatives of the
government, employers and workers is present at the conference.
</P>
