<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Publishes Report on Women's Health </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Women in the European Union (EU)
countries enjoy a high level of health and their average life
expectancy has reached 80 years, six years higher than the average
for men, an EU report said today.
</P>
<P>
The report on the state of women's health in the EU member
countries, was published by the European Commission, the EU's
executive body.
</P>
<P>
The report said that many EU women still die prematurely before
the age of 65 due to accidents or diseases, such as cancer or
cardiovascular disease, which to a large extent can be avoided by
healthier life styles or early detection.
</P>
<P>
The two largest causes of death among women are diseases of the
circulatory system, which account for 43 percent of all deaths,
and cancer which accounts for 26 percent.
</P>
<P>
EU Commissioner Padraig Flynn today said that the report was
not intended to imply that greater emphasis should be placed on
women's health compared to men's health.
</P>
<P>
But for biological, social and other reasons, it deserves
recognition that women's health concerns differ from those of men,
he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
