<HEADLINE> Malaysia Confident of Hong Kong Position: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia today expressed the
confidence that Hong Kong under the "one country, two systems"
concept would maintain its position as the world's top business
and financial hub.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's stand on the reverting of Hong Kong to China is
expected to enhance Sino-Malaysian ties, Malaysian Foreign
Minister Abdullah Ahmad Badawi told the National Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Talking to reporters later about Malaysia-Hong Kong relations,
the minister said the ties will remain unchanged when China
resumes the exercise of sovereignty over Hong Kong on July 1.
</P>
<P>
He said the assurance was given to him by his Chinese
counterpart during his recent visit to China.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the Chinese foreign minister had told him
that there would be no problems for Malaysians to visit Hong Kong
for trade and investment missions.
</P>
<P>
"Our previous privileges will be continued," he said, adding
that the Malaysian government however has not decided on the
travel documents of Malaysians wishing to visit Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"With the change in Hong Kong's status which will be known as
the Special Administrative Region of the People's Republic of
China, immigration matters will depend on our relations with
China," he said.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's commission office in Hong Kong will be known as the
consulate-general from July 1, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
