<HEADLINE> Two-thirds Ugandan Women Prefer Local Traditional </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Seventy percent of Ugandan women
prefer local traditional medicine and about 50 percent of them
select to deliver in health facilities, ''The New Vision''
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Treatment cost in modern medical facilities lay too high to
access for poor which wemen are consisting the denied majority
of, said the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
As a result of lack of fees, wemen have to learn to ignore
their suffering in endemic cases such as malaria and TB, the
report added.
</P>
<P>
Poor relationship also separates patients and modern medical
staff,medical professor Willy Anokbonggo of Makerere University
told a workshop in central Mukono District.
</P>
<P>
Traditional healers show more consideration for women then the
modern health workers, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Carol Vlassof, Manager of the special program for research and
training in tropical diseases, noted that famele patients were
often blamed for being late in reporting their cases by health
workers who didn't find out why.
</P>
<P>
The fame of modern medicine also eroded by the fact that in
some cases, treatment is forced to be stoped by the financial
burden, and inadequate information regarding the dosage and
results in the recureence of certain ailments, the report said.
</P>
</TEXT>
