<DOCNO> XIE19970603.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK's Fund Management Industry Mainly Driven by Overseas Investors: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Overseas clients accounted for
67.2 percent of the assets managed by 45 fund companies in Hong
Kong as at the end of 1996, according to a survey by the Hong Kong
Investment Funds Association (HKIFA).
</P>
<P>
By December 31, 1996, the total assets managed by HKIFA
members in Hong Kong had amounted to 101 billion US dollars,
according to the survey released here today.
</P>
<P>
Out of the total, Asia-Pacific (excluding Hong Kong) clients
accounted for about 20 percent of the total assets, while
non-Asia-Pacific clients took up 47.2 percent, the survey said.
</P>
<P>
"Unlike the United Sates, Britain and Japan where the growth of
the fund management industry has been primarily locally driven,
the development of the industry in Hong Kong has, hitherto, been
spurred by the demands of overseas investors.
</P>
<P>
"The key force that fosters the growth in Hong Kong has been
the demand by overseas clients, especially from Europe and North
America, for asset management services to capitalize on the growth
in the region," said Andrew Lo, Chairman of the HKIFA.
</P>
<P>
Among the key factors contributing to Hong Kong obtaining such
a position are, according to Lo, a free open market, respect and
pragmatic regulatory structure, professional and largely
non-interventionist regulation, a attractive tax regime,
well-developed infrastructure, abundant supply of personnel with
strong financial background and predominantly English-speaking.
</P>
<P>
And Hong Kong has been invited to host the International
Investment Funds Association conference this October. This is the
first time that the conference is to be held in Asia (outside
Japan) and it further reinforces the position of Hong Kong as a
major fund management center in Asia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
