<HEADLINE> Cleveland's Brandon Wins NBA Sportsmanship Award </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Terrell Brandon of Cleveland was
named the winner of the 1996-97 NBA Sportsmanship Award, designed
to honour a player who best represents the ideals of sportsmanship
on the court, NBA commissioner David Stern said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
To honour Brandon, the NBA will donate 25,000 US dollars to
Grant High School, his former school in Portland, Oregon.
</P>
<P>
Brandon, the Central Division nominee for this year's
Sportsmanship Award, received 55 of 115 votes from a panel
consisting of 28 national media members and three media members
who cover the NBA regularly from each of the league's 29 cities.
</P>
<P>
Atlantic Division nominee Buck Williams of New York finished
second with 24 votes. Mideast Division nominee Jeff Hornacek of
Utah and Pacific Division nominee Mitch Richmond of Sacramenton
received 20 and 16 votes respectively.
</P>
<P>
Former NBA players Dave Bing, Rolando Blackman, Billy
Cunningham, Julius Erving, Doc Rivers, and Tom "Satch" Sanders,
the NBA's vice president, selected the four divisional winners
from a pool of 29 team nominees. Each team nominated one of its
own players for this award.
</P>
<P>
The annual award is part of a larger program, the NBA
Sportsmanship Initiative, which also consists of the NBA
Student-Athlete Sportsmanship Program and a public service
compaign. The initiative focuses on fostering the ideals of
sportsmanship of ethical behavior, fair play and integrity in
amateur and professional basketball players. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
