<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sweden Tops OECD Members in Investment Outflow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Sweden was Europe's most avid
foreign investor, according to the latest statistical report of
the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development.
</P>
<P>
The 1997 edition of "OECD in Figures," based mainly on figures
from 1995, places Sweden in the first place in terms of investment
outflow, with the equivalent of 4.4 percent of its gross domestic
product (GDP) invested abroad.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Sweden ranked the fourth among 26 members of the
OECD in foreign investment, with 3.4 percent of its GDP placed
abroad.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Sweden was also an attractive place for
foreign firms to place their money. In fact, the inflow of direct
investments to Sweden exceeded the outflow.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, foreigners placed an amount equivalent to 5.9 percent
of the Swedish GDP in this country, or 13.6 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
However, the Swedish economy as a whole can hardly be described
as red-hot. The gross domestic product grew by only 1.3 percent
between 1985-1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
