<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Opium War TV Series to Be Broadcast Nationwide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 3 (Xinhua) -- A 26-part TV series about Opium
War (1840-1842) will be broadcast first in Shanghai on June 17, to
greet Hong Kong's return to China by reproducing history on the
screen.
</P>
<P>
The TV series will then be broadcast by more than 200
television stations across the country.
</P>
<P>
The Opium War, launched by the British government in June, 1840
to protect the British opium trade in China, resulted in the
signing of the Treaty of Nanjing, which forced China to cede Hong
Kong to Britain.
</P>
<P>
The TV series portrays Lin Zexu's mission of banning opium in
south China, and the subsequent repeated trials of military
strength and diplomatic contests between China and Britain.
</P>
<P>
Lin Zexu (1785-1850), a Qing Dynasty (1644-1911) lord, was
appointed imperial envoy to stamp out the opium trade being
conducted by British merchants in south China in 1839. He led the
move to ban opium in Guangzhou city, and destroyed some 20,000
cases of opium seized from British traders.
</P>
<P>
Huang Jun, director of the TV series, said that the series is
different from other movies on the same topic. Emperor Dao Guang
(1821-1850), the sixth emperor of Qing Dynasty, is the focus of
the Huang's production, after Huang reviewed the War in light of
the latest historical research.
</P>
<P>
Li Baotian will act Emperor Dao Guang and Xu Huanshan will
play Lord Lin Zexu in the TV series.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong province, where the Opium War broke out, invested 16
million yuan (1.93 million U.S. dollars) in the series. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970603.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadians Vote for Continued Fiscal Prudence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Canadian voters today gave the
Liberal Party another mandate, sending a clear message that they
want the federal government to stay the course of fiscal prudence
and sound management.
</P>
<P>
The Liberal Party won 39 percent of the national vote and 155
seats out of the 301-member House of Commons, enough to form a
majority government.
</P>
<P>
The Reform won 61 seats, the Bloc Quebecois 44, the New
Democratic 20, the Progressive Conservative 20 and others 1.
</P>
<P>
Canadian voters tonight "renewed their confidence in our teams
and programs," a jubilant Jean Chretien said to his supporters in
his riding of Saint-Maurice, Quebec.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Liberal Party will "continue to put fiscal
house in order" as it has promised in the campaign, continuing to
create jobs and improve the economy by investing in industries
of the future.
</P>
<P>
Since the last election held on October 25, 1993, when
Chretien's Liberal Party won an overwhelming majority, the
government has introduced prudent fiscal measures to slash the
deficit from 42 billion Canadian dollars (30 billion U.S. dollars)
to just over 9 billion Canadian dollars (6.5 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
It has also successfully reduced inflation and interest rates
to their lowest levels in the past three decades.
</P>
<P>
All these have improved Canada's overall economic environment
and propelled foreign and domestic business investments in the
country.
</P>
<P>
According to a recent estimate by the International Monetary
Fund, Canada would see a strongest economic growth among the G-7
countries this year and the next.
</P>
<P>
Yet, the economic policy has also produced its side effects. At
present, some 1.5 million Canadians are still jobless despite the
fact that the Liberal government has helped to create more than
770,000 jobs since it took office.
</P>
<P>
Canada's social welfare has also been slashed, which partly
explained why the Liberal Party lost 23 seats this time in the
Atlantic provinces where people are affected the most.
</P>
<P>
The government owed a lot to Canadians for their sacrifices,
Chretien said, adding that "the light at the end of the tunnel is
growing brighter."
</P>
<P>
By voting the Liberals back to office, most Canadians also
seemed to endorse Chretien's step-by-step approach to the national
unity issue.
</P>
<P>
"We promised to keep our country strong and united, and that we
will do," Chretien said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970603.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ousted S. Leonean President Speaks out Against </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Sierra Leonean President Ahmed Tejan
Kabbah on Monday spoke out against the military coup that had
toppled him, admitting that he requested the west African
peace-keeping force to intervene.
</P>
<P>
Speaking with a BBC program, Kabbah denounced the saying that
the it was irresponsible to ask for military action of ECOMOG,
west Africa's peacekeeping forces, in a very crowded and
overpopulated city.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Nigerian-led ECOMOG soldiers are
professionals and have been very selective and discrete in their
operations.
</P>
<P>
It was the Sierra Leonean rebels and coup soldiers who, in
their panic reactions, committed atrocities.
</P>
<P>
Kabbah said he was in regular contact with the Nigeria
authority and expected the intervention to be over pretty soon,
adding that he would return to his country afterwards.
</P>
<P>
He said he was pleased to hear that Secretary-General of the
United Nations, Kofi Annan, has given his support to the military
intervention.
</P>
<P>
Kabbah called the May 25 coup "a disgrace to Africa" and said
that the entire African continent was unhappy with it.
</P>
<P>
"While people are trying to move into the 21st century, some
of these guys are trying to drag us back to the 17th century.
This is not acceptable," he said.
</P>
<P>
Around 3,600 ECOMOG troops started attacks against the coup
soldiers led by Major Paul Johnny Koroma early Monday morning
upon the failure of diplomatic efforts to restore the elected
government of Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
The ECOMOG troops soon seized the Lungi airport near Freetown.
Some 32 deaths have been reported so far in the fighting.
</P>
</TEXT>
