<HEADLINE> 62 Casualties Reported in Sierra Leonean </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The intervention by the west African
peace-keeping force known as ECOMOG in Sierra Leone has resulted
in 62 casualties in the first day of the operations.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here said 32 people, including 30 civilians
and two soldiers were killed in the attacks which started in
early Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
Amid continuous ECOMOG bombardment, Major Paul Johnny Koromah
reportedly came out in Freetown for the first time in an open
vehicle, waving a white hankerchief and urging his people to
demostrate their support in condmening the military invervention.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of Sierra Leoneans took to the street, protesting
the use of force by ECOMOG.
</P>
<P>
The intervention, however, won wide support at the on-going
33rd Organization of African Unity (OAU) summit.
</P>
<P>
Kofi Annan, the United Nations Secretary-General who was at
the summit, said, "The will of the people must be the basis of
government and authority in Africa. And governments duly elected
should not be overthrown by force."
</P>
<P>
Salim Ahmed Salim, who was re-elected into the OAU
Secretary-General at the summit, said the coup in Sierra Leone is
unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
"In the interest of both Sierra Leone and Africa as a whole,
everything must be done to restore constitutional legality in
that country," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to reports, ECOMOG troops in Sierra Leone now totals
3,600, including 1,600 from Nigeria, 1,500 from Ghana and 500
from Guinea. 
</P>
</TEXT>
