<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Anxious About French Policy on Monetary Union </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Foreign ministers of the European
Union (EU) countries, who were gathering in Luxembourg for a
monthly meeting, Monday expressed their cautious optimism towards
the prospects that the new Socialist government in France would
not derail the process of European integration.
</P>
<P>
The reserved optimism reflected uncertainty over where the new
French government was heading for given that Prime Minister Lionel
Jospin had rejected the austerity required for a single currency.
</P>
<P>
One senior EU official called the result potentially "very
dangerous," adding that if the Socialists "do what they say they
will do, it will create a threat to monetary union, or start it on
a very weak basis."
</P>
<P>
Most foreign ministers are waiting to see whom Jospin will
choose as French foreign minister, which is supposed to serve as
an indicator of French policies. The appointment is expected to be
announced later this week.
</P>
<P>
They are also hoping for clues to French policy from whether
Jospin will signal a willingness to conclude a treaty on EU reform
in two weeks in Amsterdam.
</P>
<P>
However, Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini expressed his
personal satisfaction with the election results in France, saying
that the Socialist victory had increased the chances of a delay to
monetary union that would enable Rome to join a single currency at
the outset.
</P>
<P>
But Dini also said, "Italy will not be the country to demand a
change of the timetable," referring to the scheduled January 1999
launching date for the single currency euro. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
