<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0900 GMT, June 3 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA -- Canada's ruling Liberal Party has won enough seats to
form a second majority government in a general election held
today. This will be the first time in the past 44 years that the
Liberals has formed a back-to-back majority government, the CBC
Television reported.
</P>
<P>
NAIROBI -- The daily newspaper Kenya Times today said in a
commentary that "African today suffers more from failure of
imported economic and political models than from problems
engendered by local leadership." The paper run by the ruling
Kenya African National Union (KANU) called on African peoples to
be alert to Western "advice" on the transformation of political
and economic models.
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- A Harvard University scholar has called for a
halt to concocting China as a new threat, warning that it will
have "dangerous consequences for U.S. policy." "China is a rising
power, but it need not to be an enemy," Ezra F. Vogel, a Henry
Ford professor of the social sciences and director of the Fairbank
Center at Harvard University, said in an article in the
International Herald Tribune last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
MANILA -- Three brothers and their sisters, all minors, were
killed Monday when a grenade they were playing exploded in a
village in the southern Philippines, the Philippine News Agency
reported today.
</P>
<P>
BANGKOK -- Thailand is expected to export 23 billion baht (920
million U.S. dollars) worth of diamonds this year, an increase of
13.7 percent over last year, a leading Thai research institute
predicted. The diamond exports will account for 40 percent of the
country's total jewelry exports this year, according to the Thai
Farmers Research Center.
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States, in reaction of a U.N. proposal
of renewing the Iraqi "oil-for-food" deal, said Monday that it
would need time for consideration for that proposal. "We will
study the issue closely and make our determination closer to the
time of renewal," State Department spokesman John Dinger told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- The Iranian government said that it has closed its
embassy in Kabul and its diplomats have left the Afghan capital.
Mahmoud Mohammadi, spokesman of the Iranian Foreign Ministry,
said that the aim of the Iranian embassy, which had remained open
after most countries closed their missions in Kabul, was to
provide assistance to the Afghan people.
</P>
<P>
SARAJEVO -- Nato-led Stablization Force (SFOR) said Monday that
senior officers from its backup forces are visiting Bosnia this
week on a reconnaissance tour. "This reconnaissance is designed to
enable them to gain a clear picture of the requirements should
Nato decide to deploy the SFOR Strategic Reserve (SSR)," SFOR
Spokesman Major Chris Riley said.
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The election of the Socialist government in
France will not influence the U.S.-French relations, the White
House said Monday. White House Spokesman Michael McCurry said the
U.S. would "work closely" with a new French government, which is
to be formed by Lionel Jospin, the elected prime minister.
</P>
<P>
MANILA -- A news editor was killed at dawn today by an
unidentified gunman inside an abandoned taxicab in a northern
Manila suburb, police said. Initial investigation said Danny
Hernandez, 52, was shot in the head when riding the taxi home
from his editorial office of the People's Tonight, a tabloid in
Metro Manila. 
</P>
