<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-03 09:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian Envoy to Brief U.S. on Shuttle Diplomacy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian envoy Osama el-Baz flew to
Washington this morning to meet U.S. officials on the deadlocked
Mideast peace process, the Egyptian MENA news agency reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Baz, political advisor to President Hosni Mubarak, is expected
to brief the U.S. administration on his latest shuttle trips to
mediate between the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) and Israel
in the past few days, diplomatic sources here said.
</P>
<P>
He has been mediating between the two sides in a bid to bring
them back to the negotiating table since Mubarak met Israeli Prime
Minister Binyamin Netanyahu in Egyptian Red Sea resort of Sharm
el-Sheikh last Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"Egypt's role was not to present Egyptian proposals to the
Palestinian and Israeli sides but it sought to narrow the gap
between the parties in response to a request from the Palestinian
leadership," he told reporters Monday.
</P>
<P>
"There should be a movement to break the deadlock," Baz said,
expressing the hope that a breakthrough would be achieved in the
coming period.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have made resumption of the peace talks
conditional on Israel's halt of Har Homa, a new Jewish settlement
Israel started to build in March sparking a two-month-old crisis
in the Mideast peace process. Netanyahu has refused to budge.
</P>
<P>
During his latest shuttle tour that ended Sunday, the Egyptian
envoy went to Israel to continue talks with Netanyahu and met
later with head of the Palestinian negotiating team Saeb Erekat.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu's office hailed "some progress" toward solving the
problems between the PNA and Israel at the meeting, but a
Palestine Liberation Organization (PLO) official who spoke on
condition of anonymity said "Baz did not get responses from the
Israeli side to Palestinian demand."
</P>
<P>
U.S. Ambassador to Egypt Edward Walker has reiterated Egypt's
pivotal role in pushing forward the Mideast peace process and
eliminating obstacles in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Walker said Sunday the enormous Egyptian efforts were highly
respected and appreciated by the American and global public
opinions.
</P>
<P>
U.S. envoy Dennis Ross made two shuttle trips to the region
last month, but failed to bridge the gap between the Palestinian
and Israeli positions.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians accused Ross of pro-Israeli bias and called
for higher-level U.S. intervention. But Washington was
unresponsive. U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said last
weekend that it was up to the two parties to show the political
will to end the impasse themselves.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, Jordan and Egypt both affirmed the importance of
the U.S. role in peacemaking.
</P>
<P>
Israel and Egypt, the first Arab country to make peace with
Israel in 1979, have been the two largest beneficiaries of the
U.S. aid. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
