<DOCNO> XIE19970603.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Scholar Urges Halt to Concocting China as New Threat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 2 (Xinhua) -- A Harvard University scholar has
called for a halt to concocting China as a new threat, warning that
it will have "dangerous consequences for U.S. policy."
</P>
<P>
"China is a rising power, but it need not to be an enemy,"
Ezra F. Vogel, a Henry Ford professor of the social sciences and
director of the Fairbank Center at Harvard University, said in an
article in the International Herald Tribune last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Vogel said the reader of much of the U.S. press has little idea
on the fundamental changes taking place in China. But instead of
reporting China's progress, the U.S. media, including The New
Republic and The Weekly Standard, are trumpeting that China is
emerging as a great new threat.
</P>
<P>
The trumpeting has created a mood that makes reasoned policy
discussion difficult in the United States, the professor said in
his article "Don't Let Scare-Mongering Make China a Foe."
</P>
<P>
"Is it in the U.S. interest to create 1.2 billion enemies in a
country likely to be the world's largest economy within a couple
of decades," he asked.
</P>
<P>
"If we treat China as an enemy, we increases the chances of
creating an enemy."
</P>
<P>
Vogel said nearly one-fifth of the U.S. Congress has visited
China in the last few months, but many representatives are afraid
to report their impression publicly for fear of being accused by
the press.
</P>
<P>
"I see what all other experienced observers of China see --
progress not only in economic well-being but in free expression of
opinion," said Vogel, who said he has visited China at least once
a year since 1979 and often returned to the same universities,
villages and factories he visited.
</P>
<P>
He listed as examples "the growth of village elections and
voices of dissent in the National People's Congress (parliament),
the increase of information and varied opinions, the spread of the
rule of law, the adaptation to international institutions, the
outspokeness of the Hong Kong vernacular press."
</P>
<P>
The scholar urged the U.S. press to end its ridiculous and
extreme reporting on China, which misleads the U.S. audience. The
American audience hopes for more balanced reporting, he said.
</P>
<P>
Vogel expressed his support to the effort by U.S. President
Bill Clinton and thoughtful members of both parties of Congress to
work with China.
</P>
<P>
"Whipping up a China threat will have dangerous consequences
for U.S. policy," he said. "We cannot deal with many of the big
global issues -- trade, proliferation of nuclear weapons,
conventional arms control, environmental management -- without the
cooperation of all of the world's largest economies."
</P>
<P>
He noted that even at the peak of the Cold War, the U.S. had to
work closely with the former Soviet Union to reduce the risk of
conflict.
</P>
<P>
"We need to work much more with China, a far more successful
economy, to deal with the problems of an increasingly
interdependent world," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970603.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Government to Assist Disabled Climb </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The Ministry of Natural
Resources and Tourism is to assist Mashaka Nyanzai, a disabled,
in his Mount Kilimanjaro charity climbing which is to take place
in October this year, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Minister Zakia Meghji told reportes here recently in the city
that her ministry will provide Nyanzai with the equipments needed
for climbing, fees and a tour operator.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, she congratulated Nyanzi for his decision which
will raise funds for establishing a recreation center and a
revolving fund for the disabled people in Dar es Salaam.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, while presenting his request to the minister, Nyanzai
said the project which is his own brain child needs some 1.5
million US Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Nyanzai said with the number of disabled totaling about three
million in Tanzania today, he has found that the charity to climb
Mount Kilimanjaro will enable him raise funds enough to run the
project.
</P>
<P>
Explaining the aim of the project to the minister, he said its
emphasis will be giving loans to disabled people from the
revolving funds, adding that another objective is to make sure
that disabled people participate in games, computer knowledge and
health care at a cheap cost.  
</P>
