<HEADLINE> PKK Leader: PKK to Attack Israeli, U.S. Targets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 3 (Xinhua) -- A leader of the Kurdistan Workers'
Party (PKK) has said here that his group will attack Israeli and
U.S. targets in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Khalil Attachi, the PKK's military leader, was quoted by
Beirut's newspaper the Daily Star today as saying that Turkey's
cities and tourist areas will also be targets of his party's
operations.
</P>
<P>
Attachi, whose separatist guerrillas are being chased by
Turkish troops in northern Iraq, said that he will "carry out
operations against Israeli targets in Istanbul and elsewhere in
Turkey and against U.S. enemy interests."
</P>
<P>
About 25,000 to 50,000 Turkish troops began the cross-border
military operation in Northern Iraq in May 14 to attack the
outlawed PKK, which has fought a 13-year separatist war in
southeast Turkey for an independent Kurdish state.
</P>
<P>
Attachi told a press conference in Beirut's Shiite southern
suburb Monday that the Turkish troops which invaded northern
Iraq were trained in Israel as part of the Israel-Turkish
military training agreement signed in February 1996.
</P>
<P>
"This campaign is against the people of the area in general
and only serves the interests of Turkey, Israel and the United
States, who are linked by a strategic alliance," Attachi added.
</P>
<P>
Turkish military officials have said more than 2,000 PKK
members have been killed in the fighting in northern Iraq, but
the PKK claimed its losses are less than 100. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
