<HEADLINE> Canada's Liberal Party to Form Majority Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Canada's ruling Liberal Party has
won enough seats to form a second majority government in a general
election held today.
</P>
<P>
This will be the first time in the past 44 years that the
Liberals has formed a back-to-back majority government, the CBC
Television reported.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary results showed that Jean Chretien's Liberal Party
won 155 seats out of a total of 301 seats in Canada's House of
Commons.
</P>
<P>
The Liberals were followed by the Reform Party with 61 seats;
the Bloc Quebecois, 44 seats; the New Democratic Party, 20; the
Progressive Conservative, 20; and others 1.
</P>
<P>
The Reform will displace the separatist Bloc Quebecois as the
largest opposition group in the next parliament.
</P>
<P>
The polls here opened at 9:30 a.m. (local time) and close at
9:30 p.m.. The official results of the election has yet to come
out.
</P>
<P>
Across the country, there are about 19 million registered
voters, many of them may not have come out and voted at the end of
the five-week campaign.
</P>
<P>
In last election held on October 25, 1993, the Liberals won 177
seats in the then 295-member parliament.
</P>
<P>
The separatist Bloc Quebecois won 54 seats, the Reform Party
52, the New Democratic Party 9 and the Progressive Conservative
2. 
</P>
</TEXT>
