<DOCNO> XIE19970603.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-03 08:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian Archaeological Exhibition Opens in Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Israeli President Ezer Weizman
said that archaeological finds in Egypt provide proof that Jews
and Arabs can live together in harmony, The Jerusalem Post
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Weizman made the remark Monday night when he opened an
exhibition at the Israel Museum in Jerusalem. On display are
documents discovered from the Cairo Geniza, a repository for
timeworn sacred manuscripts and ritual objects.
</P>
<P>
The Geniza was uncovered in the Old Cairo suburb of Fustat,
with some 90,000 manuscripts found.
</P>
<P>
The documents were later identified by Solomon Schechter of
Cambridge University in 1897. This vast collection of liturgical,
legal, commercial and literary documents generally revolutionized
the study of the medieval history of Palestinian and Middle
Eastern Jewry.
</P>
<P>
Among the highlights of the exhibition are hand-written texts
dating back to the 11th century. There is a corrected version of
a page from The Perplexed Guide by Moses Maimonides, a Jewish
philosopher whose contributions in religion, philosophy and
medicine have influenced Jewish and non-Jewish scholars alike.
</P>
<P>
The texts are written in Hebrew, Judeo-Arabic, Arabic and
Yiddish.
</P>
<P>
In the main, the documents describe the everyday life of the
vibrant medieval Jewish communities in the Mediterranean
basin. There are references of bridal dowries and land tracts,
and lists of household items. There are also pharmaceutical
prescriptions and medical remedies.
</P>
<P>
Some 50 fragments from the cache of documents found in 1897
are on loan to the museum, almost all of them from the Cambridge
University Library. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970603.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Longest Fossil Ivory Found In Hubei </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The longest piece of fossilized ivory
in the world, has been recently unearthed in Shongzi city in
central China's Hubei Province.
</P>
<P>
The 3.26-meter ivory belonged to an elephant that lived
250,000-700,000 years ago. The fossil is two centimeters longer
than the one unearthed in Danjiangkou in Hubei Province.
</P>
<P>
The research on the ivory will provide important information on
paleontology, geology, and archeology. 
</P>
