<DOCNO> XIE19970603.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africans Urged to Be Alert to Western "Advice" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The daily newspaper Kenya Times
today said in a commentary that "African today suffers more from
failure of imported economic and political models than from
problems engendered by local leadership."
</P>
<P>
The paper run by the ruling Kenya African National Union
(KANU) called on African peoples to be alert to Western "advice"
on the transformation of political and economic models.
</P>
<P>
At present, the paper said, the one party government system
has given way to multiplicity politics in a number of countries
on African continent.
</P>
<P>
However, "there is little evidence of success for the policies
advanced by some Western powers to bring about political
integration and economic growth in most African nations", it
noted.
</P>
<P>
The daily paper pointed out that African economies had
steadfastly declined in the last seven years pushing the once
promising nations into greater debt burden.
</P>
<P>
The understanding of the ailing continent by the World Bank
and the International Monetary Fund "have been miserably poor",
the local newspaper stressed.
</P>
<P>
The commentary stated that "the continent's future must be
decided not by an international policy system but by the
indigenous leaders and peoples of each independent African
state."
</P>
<P>
Homegrown economic and political ideas can help reverse
Africa's decline, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
It added that "social studies have shown that a people's
attitude towards life is fundamental to social, political and
economic advancement and a vital catalyst in achieving the
Africa's dream of integration."
</P>
<P>
Kenya, like many other African countries, is a victim of this
forced transformation, the ruling party paper noted.
</P>
<P>
According to a report by the local weekly paper The East
African, some of the Western envoys accredited to Nairobi are
likely to seek a meeting with Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi to
clarify government's promises about the conduct of Kenya's
forthcoming General Elections.
</P>
<P>
In April this year, some Western diplomats privately made
public their concerns about a free and fair election in Kenya and
the Kenyan government responded with a statement criticizing
their interference in its internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
Referring to seeking audience with President Moi, the
commentary noted that "we highly doubt their motives".
</P>
<P>
"Some of the envoys have been playing it very dirty behind the
President's back under the guise of promoting political education
and democratic awareness in the country", it stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
