<HEADLINE> Philippine House Speaker to Run for Presidency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Philippine House Speaker Jose de
Venecia said today he has decided to run for the Presidency in
1998 with or without the appointment of President Fidel Ramos.
</P>
<P>
De Venecia made the remarks when swearing in all village
officials elected last month in Pangasinan province in the
northern Philippines. However, he said he still needs the help of
the President.
</P>
<P>
Local media said earlier that the support of President Ramos
would help a candidate win an additional 20 percent of votes in
next year's national elections.
</P>
<P>
De Venecia, meanwhile, also said he would personally sponsor
the entry of Defense Secretary Renato de Villa to the ruling
Lakas-NUCD, although he admitted that de Villa will be a main
rival for him in the 1998 polls.
</P>
<P>
De Villa announced his decision to participate in the
presidential election over the weekend. But he has to join the
ruling party first before being appointed by President Ramos.
</P>
<P>
Asked on Senator Leticia Ramos Shahani, another aspirant for
the Presidency, de Venecia said he foresees his reconciliation
later with the President's sister.
</P>
<P>
Shahani has challenged de Venecia to relinquish the post of the
secretary general of the ruling party to level the playing ground
in the selection of the party's standard bearer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
