<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-03 07:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jewish Organization Demands Eastern European </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 3 (Xinhua) -- A Jewish organization is
threatening to obstruct the inclusion of Poland, Romania and
Czech Republic into North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) if
they refuse to return Jewish property confiscated during the war.
</P>
<P>
The World Jewish Restitution Organization (WJRO) made the
decision at its council meeting held Monday night in
Jerusalem. It vowed to use its influence to work against the
acceptance by NATO of the three above-mentioned countries if they
do not return the Jewish assets.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, the WJRO also decided to establish a
committee that would report within a month on how to
distribute the Swiss humanitarian fund to Holocaust survivors.
</P>
<P>
The committee, which comprises representatives of the World
Jewish Congress (WJC), Jewish Agency and the American Jewish
Joint Distribution Committee, was instructed to make aid to
Holocaust survivors in Eastern Europe its top priority.
</P>
<P>
There are some 60,000 Holocaust survivors in Eastern Europe,
according to the Center of Organizations of Holocaust Survivors
in Israel. Some other organizations believe the figure is much
higher.
</P>
<P>
WJRO's vice-chairman Naphtali Lavie hoped his group would
distribute the compensation funds in Europe. But WJC disagreed
with the WJRO, saying that Israel must be the focal point
for financial distributions worldwide.
</P>
<P>
WJC chairman in Israel Mati Droblas said these payments
would be to establish old-age homes in the former Soviet
Union and to construct community centers for Holocaust survivors
throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
Under strong pressures from Israel and Jewish organizations
worldwide, Switzerland, which is accused of dealing with the
gold looted from Jews by German Nazis in the Second World
War, agreed earlier this year to create a 50 million dollar
compensation fund for the Holocaust survivors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
