<DOCNO> XIE19970603.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tobacco Advertisements Banned in Weihai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Six city departments in Weihai, a
port city in east China's Shandong Province, have jointly set
forth a proposal to forbid tobacco advertisements in the city, the
Shanghai-based "Wenhui Daily" reported.
</P>
<P>
The proposal requires all local working units and citizens to
abide by the "Advertisement Law" and the "Provisional Regulations
For Tobacco Advertisement".
</P>
<P>
No tobacco advertisement should be seen in public places, and
working units should refuse any activities sponsored by tobacco
businessmen.
</P>
<P>
The proposal also asks advertising agencies not to deal with
tobacco advertisements, and citizens not to carry items bearing
tobacco brands.
</P>
<P>
The move is part of the city's efforts to qualify as one of the
countries' "health cities". Several other cities also have taken
the same action against tobacco advertising. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
