<DOCNO> XIE19970603.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt's Population Rises to Over 61 Million </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Egypt's population has risen by 21.7
percent compared with a decade ago to reach 61.45 million in
1996, making it the 17th most populous country in the world, the
Egyptian Gazette reported today.
</P>
<P>
In the 1986 census, the population was 50.504 million, said
Ahab Moustafa Elwi, head of the Central Agency for Public
Mobilization and Statistics (CAPMAS) at the briefing on the
preliminary results of a national census conducted every 10 years
on population, housing and installations.
</P>
<P>
The latest census was conducted by officials from different
ministries and local government agencies, said Elwi.
</P>
<P>
Despite the large population increase, the population growth
had fallen to 2.1 percent in 1996 from 2.8 percent in 1986, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Gender divisions remained steady in this census, with males
dominating the population at 51.2 percent against 48.8 percent
females.
</P>
<P>
The population in Cairo, the capital, stands at 16.79 million
with an increase of 11.9 percent over 1986.
</P>
<P>
While inhabitants of rural areas mushroomed at an annual rate
of 2.26 percent during the 10 years between the two censuses,
urban areas had lower growth rates at 1.85 percent.
</P>
<P>
Only 3.5 percent of Egyptians live outside the country and the
number of illiterates dropped by a significant 38.6 percent over
1986 to 17.35 million, according to the census which was
conducted for six months from June 1, 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970603.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Extend Life of Panda Sperm by Li Xiguang and Zhou Qian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Scientists have developed a liquid
which adds at least 20 hours to the life of the in vitro sperm of
the giant panda, boosting the chance of impregnating the panda by
artificial insemination.
</P>
<P>
The invention of the thawing and culture solution was made by a
research group led by Professor Chen Dayuan at the Institute of
Zoology under the Chinese Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
"Under the protection of the liquid, the frozen sperm of giant
panda has been able to live up to 21 hours outside of the animal's
body, as opposed to one hour and a half previously," Professor Chen
said.
</P>
<P>
"The discovery has dramatically raised the success rate of
artificial insemination for the giant panda," he added.
</P>
<P>
According to the Chinese researcher, 24 giant panda cubs, had
been born in six years between 1990 and 1995 from artificial
insemination techniques using sperm that was stored in the new
solution. Most of the panda cubs were twins.
</P>
<P>
Previously, the thawing and culture solution used in artificial
insemination of giant pandas was the same solution used for the
artificial insemination of dairy cows.
</P>
<P>
"Frozen sperm of the giant panda could only live from two
minutes to one hour and a half in the old solution," he noted,
"although a few cubs had been born, the success rate was poor."
</P>
<P>
"The new solution, at the proper pH level, osmotic pressure,
and temperature, will effectively preserve the viability of the
sperm after thawing," he said.
</P>
<P>
"In the past, the old solution had made most sperm 'drunk',
and lose their motility upon entering the female panda, and even
lose their viability," Professor Chen said.
</P>
<P>
The research paper of Chen and his group has been published in
the latest English-edition of "Chinese Science Bulletin," the
leading scientific journal in China.
</P>
<P>
The giant panda is the world's best-known endangered species
which can only be found in the mountains of southwest China. Its
population stands at less than 1,000.
</P>
<P>
The giant panda normally gets pregnant once a year and produces
one or two babies at each birth.
</P>
<P>
"The female pandas always show indifference and contempt to the
approaching male giant pandas during the mating season," said
Professor Zhang Anju, a co-author of the paper.
</P>
<P>
"So it's very difficult to have them mate and get pregnant
naturally," he said, adding that "only 10 percent of giant pandas
are able to mate naturally."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970603.0204 </DOCNO>
