<DOCNO> XIE19970603.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Farm Machinery Brings Better Harvest to Northeast China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Better harvests brought by
improved farming mechanization have encouraged farmers in
northeast China's Liaoning Province to invest heavily in farm
machinery.
</P>
<P>
The province has 9.5 million kw of mechanical power capacity,
including more than 160,000 tractors and 150,000 other supporting
farm tools and processing equipment. Its farm machinery sales
exceed two billion yuan annually.
</P>
<P>
Mechanical cultivation saved farmers 27 million kg of seeds,
increased grain output by nearly 400 million kg last year, and
brought about one billion yuan in economic results, according to
the provincial agricultural machinery administrative department.
</P>
<P>
Sales and use of large and medium-sized farm machinery had
decreased since China adopted the contract household
responsibility system in the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
But booming township enterprises have employed a great number
of rural surplus laborers, resulting in fewer farmers working on
more farmland. Farm machinery is again popular, and now more than
70 percent of the province's farmland is ploughed by machines.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning has taken preferential policies to promote
agricultural mechanization. One example is that the local
government provides 30,000 yuan of financial subsidies for the
renewal of one large-scale tractor. As a result, farmers bought or
restored 2,000 tractors last year.
</P>
<P>
Factories have also shifted part of their production to small
agricultural machinery, which is more suitable for household
farming. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970603.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Salim Re-elected OAU Secretary-General </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Dr. Salim Ahmed Salim, incumbent
Secretary-General of the 53-member Organization of African Unity
(OAU), has been re-elected for a third four-year term.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made after a cast of ballot by African heads
of state and government at a closed-door session last night
during their three-day 33rd summit meeting.
</P>
<P>
Salim, who won by 37 votes out of 47, met no challenge as Cote
D'Ivoire's Foreign Minister Amara Essy, who had earlier indicated
interest in the post, withdrew.
</P>
<P>
Ibrahim Dagash, spokesman of the OAU secretariat, said Essy
decided to withdraw because he did not want to cause division
within the continental body.
</P>
<P>
Francophone African countries had been insisting on Essy's
taking over of Salim who comes from English-speaking Tanzania, but
Anglophone African countries supported Salim to serve a third
term.
</P>
<P>
Five countries of the 53-member organization did not vote
because they are under sanctions for failing to pay arrears to the
organization, while Somalia was not represented at the summit.
</P>
<P>
Six countries voted against Salim, while two abstained and
another two spoiled their ballots.
</P>
<P>
Salim, one of Africa's most outstanding diplomats, has been
committed to turning OAU, which had been branded as the mere
talk-show body before he served the first term as the
secretary-general in 1989, into a meaningful continental body
worth of note in the world.
</P>
<P>
With his leadership, OAU has been playing an increasingly
important role in raising Africa's general status in the world
scene, solving the continent's own political problems, and
pushing forward the process of Africa's regional economic
integration.
</P>
<P>
It was Salim who introduced a sanction system of barring
countries falling short of financial contributions from any
decision-making and voting sessions, a system that has helped
reduce OAU's debts significantly while boosting its coffers.
</P>
<P>
He also successfully lobbied for the creation of a conflict
prevention mechanism within OAU, which is now playing an
increasing role in seeking peaceful solutions to the continent's
wars and conflicts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
