<DOCNO> XIE19970603.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-03 07:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Smoking Kills 15 Israelis Daily: Health Ministry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 3 (Xinhua) -- An average of 15 Israelis die a
day due to smoking, Israeli Health Ministry said today.
</P>
<P>
Israel is marking the World No-Tobacco Day today. Although
foreign countries marked the day last Saturday, Israel delayed
it to today because Saturday is Shabath, the Jewish day of rest
when no office is permitted.
</P>
<P>
According to the Health Ministry, 28 percent of the 5.7
million Israeli population -- 32 percent of men and 25 percent of
women -- are smokers. Tobacco kills half of the regular users.
</P>
<P>
Latest statistics showed that smokers aged 30 to 40 are six
times more likely than non-smokers to suffer a heart attack at
that age. And 30 percent of all cancers diagnosed in Israel are
related to smoking, either by the person himself or the result
of exposure to others' smoking.
</P>
<P>
The main reasons Israeli smokers give for their habit are
addiction, tension and nervousness, the ministry said. But
nearly six out of 10 smokers have tried to quit smoking.
</P>
<P>
The Health Ministry will mark the No-Tobacco Day by cracking
down on violations of the law that restricts smoking in the
workplaces and prohibits smoking in public places and in
non-smoking sections of cafes and restaurants.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the ministry opened a telephone hot-line on
quitting smoking today in coordination with Israel Cancer
Association in order to help those smokers who intend to quit
but face difficulties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
