<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: When Chinese Farmers Go to Court...(1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Zhang Yimou became a court hero after
his masterpiece "Qiuju Goes to Court" won a medal at a major
international film festival.
</P>
<P>
The gifted Chinese director described how Qiuju, an ordinary
but brave rural woman, played by Gong Li, filed a suit against a
village head who badly beat her husband.
</P>
<P>
Some commentators say that it was the artist who helped Qiuju
win the case.
</P>
<P>
But Zhang's movie is based on a true story in Anhui province.
</P>
<P>
The question is: when Chinese farmers seek to solve their
problems in court, what else happens besides the shooting of a
movie?
</P>
<P>
"The society in which personal power overweights legal system
is coming to an end," said Fu Hongping, director of the Office for
Popularizing Law Knowledge in Anhui province, in east China.
</P>
<P>
"As ordinary persons, how could we bring a law suit against an
official before? We could just have the matter on our minds," said
Peng Chenggui, a farmer.
</P>
<P>
But Peng is able to do it today.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, a highway was built in Peng's village and it occupied
the farmers' lands. According to the government policy, the
villagers should be paid 3,000 yuan as resettlement fees for each.
</P>
<P>
But Peng only got half of the money, and the rest was kept by
government officials.
</P>
<P>
Enraged by the officials' malfeasance, Peng and 25 fellow
villagers went to the court to demand justice. They finally got it.
</P>
<P>
Artists like Zhang Yimou now can find more examples to enrich
their stories.
</P>
<P>
Kongdian village is another small village in Anhui. After a
selfish village cadre granted 14 hectares of farmlands to his
family members for private use, 122 unhappy families brought the
case to the local court.
</P>
<P>
"We farmers are now having a good taste of what is given by
law," said Xu Zhifu after winning the case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970603.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: When Farmers Go to Court...(2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
But things were quite different before.
</P>
<P>
For thousands of years in China, traditions rigidly dictated
that clan power was the main force to deal with personal relations
in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Then came the administrative power that arrived with modern
politics. Government cadres who explain policies manipulated
farmers' life and fate to a large extent.
</P>
<P>
All this derived from the old Confucian doctrine that citizens
are humble and officials are respectable.
</P>
<P>
The changes are said to be a result of a program to popularize
legal knowledge across China since 1990, when the country's
Administrative Prosecutorial Law went into effect.
</P>
<P>
Experts said that the better enforcement of laws does benefit
economic operations, which is the nation's central work nowadays.
</P>
<P>
Mi Yucai is a farmer who did spare time handcraft work to earn
money. She signed a contract with a local factory to which she
could sell her products. However, the contract was not honored
because the factory thought Mi was just a humble farmer -- a
nobody.
</P>
<P>
The factory would not dared to have done so if it had known
that Mi had employed a law advisor. The advisor subsequently
brought the case to the court. The judge's verdict was that some
600,000 yuan should be repaid to Mi to recover her economic losses.
</P>
<P>
Contacting law experts has become commonplace now among
farmers. In Ningdu County in east China's Jiangxi province, 3,000
farmers have employed law advisors. In Zhenghe County in east
China's Fujian province, the number is 1,000.
</P>
<P>
"Farmers' legal consciousness has awakened," said Ren Jianxin,
president of the Supreme People's Court of China, "Everyone is
equal before the law."
</P>
<P>
Wang Zhaoyao, deputy-governor of Anhui, said that the
government now handle affairs according to both policies and the
law. But previously they relied on policies alone.
</P>
<P>
One result is that more officials are being supervised by
citizens.
</P>
<P>
Is the change transforming China into a lawful society? Social
scientists wait for the answer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970603.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
