<HEADLINE> Import of Garment Raw Materials Allowed in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The Indian government is planning
to have a special scheme to allow garment exporters in the country
to import raw materials for pushing up value addition in price,
Textiles Ministry sources said here today.
</P>
<P>
"The Ministry of Textiles has responded positively to the
demand of exporters to allow such imports including high class
fiber. this is going to help exporters of apparel to compete
internationally," said Chairman of the Apparel Export Promotion
Council (AEPC) K.L. Madan Monday.
</P>
<P>
India's garment export figures made available for April 1997
indicated that there had been a negative growth of 14.75 percent
in US dollar value terms for garment exports, while the growth
rate in terms of quantity was 0.60 percent, he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that this indicated an alarming fall in unit value
realization and the fact that Indian exporters were still catering
to cheaper goods. Under these circumstances, the new scheme being
worked out by the government could prove a boon for garment
exporters.
</P>
<P>
The country's garment exporters had sufficient entrepreneurial
skills to double exports by the year 2002 to 9.5 billion US
dollars, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The new scheme may take into consideration some suggestions
that garment exporters be allowed to import upto 2 percent of
their export earnings in the previous year of raw materials
without any import duty and any import licence, the same sources
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
