<HEADLINE> APEC Insurance Training Program Launched </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 3 (Xinhua) -- A training program was launched
here today for managers of export credit firms from countries and
regions of the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) forum.
</P>
<P>
The ten-day program, the first of a series of five APEC trade
and investment insurance training programs, was sponsored by the
Chinese Ministry of Personnel and organized by the Export-Import
Bank of China (EximBank).
</P>
<P>
Chinese participants included people in export credits or
similar business from the EximBank, the People's Insurance Company
of China's (Group) Property Co. Ltd, China Pacific Insurance
Company, and colleges that offer insurance courses, while overseas
participants were from Indonesia, the Philippines, and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Instructors for the program were insurance experts from APEC
countries and regions such as Japan, the United States, Australia,
Canada, Singapore, and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The training programs, with four others scheduled to be held in
China's Shanghai and Indonesia, the Philippines, and Thailand,
were first suggested by the Chinese Ministry of Personnel and
supported by agencies in Japan, the United States, Canada,
Australia, Indonesia, the Philippines, Thailand, and Brunei.
</P>
<P>
Approved by an APEC meeting for developing human resources and
by the Eighth APEC ministerial meeting, the multi-lateral
cooperative training project is the largest in APEC history in
terms of the amount of funds allocated by the regional forum.
</P>
<P>
The training programs are aimed at promoting trade and
investment liberalization among APEC members.
</P>
<P>
China's EximBank was one of the country's three policy-oriented
banks founded in April of 1994 to finance exports of capital goods
such as machinery, electronics, and complete sets of equipment.
</P>
<P>
The bank's business in export credit insurance has grown
steadily in past years. The insured value of export credits last
year reached 600 million US dollars, a surge of 275 percent over
1995.  
</P>
</TEXT>
