<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's Rubber Production Increases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's rubber production
increased by 6 percent to 112 million kilograms in 1996 over 1995
and recorded the best production figure during the past decade,
according to the latest figures from the country's central bank.
</P>
<P>
The bank attributes the improvement in production to well
distributed rainfall, increased fertilizer and better management.
</P>
<P>
Rubber is one of the three major traditional exports of Sri
Lanka, occupying an important position in the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
However, bank sources stated that rubber production has shown a
declining trend during the past decade.
</P>
<P>
This is because the land under cultivation has been reduced as
more land has been used for residential and industrial purposes,
the sources explained.  
</P>
</TEXT>
