<HEADLINE> Indian Minister Visits Germany for More Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Indian Finance Minister P.
Chidambaram is leaving here today on a three-day official visit to
Germany for more economic aid from it, a government official said
here today.
</P>
<P>
India has shown its concern over declining aid from Germany in
the past few years and plans to make a strong case for more aid
from that country.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics available here, fresh aid
commitments from Germany have been coming down since 1991 and it
had taken a nosedive in 1997 when it was reduced to 220 million
German marks (127.6 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The German side made a commitment of 792.50 million marks
(396.25 million US dollars) including reprogrammed amount from
previous years and a fresh commitment of commercial credit of 450
million marks (261 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Chidambaram is expected to use his visit opportunity to make a
strong plea for a substantial step up of the German commitment
during the next year, the same official said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
