<DOCNO> XIE19970603.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Novelist Examines Farm Life </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Unlike many novelists in the 1990s
who have focussed on the lives of urban business types, Zhao Defa
chose to write a novel about the fate of the Chinese farmer.
</P>
<P>
Zhao Defa, 42, said that his intention is to preserve a vivid
picture of China's old-style farmers "who will disappear in the
coming century".
</P>
<P>
The 400,000-character "Linger on or Say Goodbye" will be a new
epic in contemporary Chinese literature, as it depicts the largest
farming population on the planet with unprecedented depth,
publishers from the People's Literature Publishing House said.
</P>
<P>
Chinese farmers' traditional life changed in the late 1970s
when the contract household responsibility system was introduced,
which tied production and income together as part of the reform
and opening-up drive. The reform also enabled farmers to set up
privately-owned rural and township factories and to move into
cities for more lucrative jobs.
</P>
<P>
Previous literary masterpieces on Chinese farmers could be
found in the 1950s and 1960s featuring class struggle and the
planned economy in rural areas. Other great works touched the
revolution which deprived the landlords of their properties and
gave them to farmers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970603.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> High-tech Industrial Belt to Appear Along China's Wanjiang River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Anhui Province, east China, plans to
set up a high-tech industrial belt along the Wanjiang River, an
800-km section of the Yangtze, a local official said.
</P>
<P>
As early as in 1990, the province worked out a strategy to
develop Wanjiang to keep pace with China's large-scale development
of the Pudong New Area in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the comprehensive economic strength of the
areas along Wanjiang has increased. Infrastructure facilities have
improved and overseas investors are flocking in, paving the way
for the setting up of a high-tech industrial belt.
</P>
<P>
By the end of this century, the combined output value
generated by high-tech industries in Wuhu, Maanshan, Tongling, and
Anqing, is expected to comprise 15 percent of the total industrial
output value of the enterprises at or above the county level in
the four cities. While the share in other cities or prefectures is
expected to increase by up to four percentage points.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, technological improvement in the the area along
Wangjiang will contribute up to 50 percent of the development of
industry and agriculture.
</P>
<P>
The area will place emphasis on four new industries such as
new materials, electronic information, electro-mechanical
products, and bio-technology, generating a combined output value
of 13 billion yuan (about 1.6 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
It will also use high technology to renovate traditional
industries, and build an economic and technological development
zone in Wuhu and a non-state-owned high-tech industrial zone in
Anqing.
</P>
<P>
In order to push the development of the industrial belt along
the river, the provincial government will pour capital into the
belt and provide favorable policies to lure technology and
industries elsewhere into the belt.
</P>
<P>
Economic analysts said that the belt, together with Shanghai
and the Suzhou-Wuxi-Changzhou high-tech industrial belts, will
jointly form a Yangtze hi-tech industrial corridor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970603.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal, India Agree on Size of Joint Hydro Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Nepal and India have agreed on
the size of a joint multi-purpose hydro project on their border
river with a view to maximizing its benefit, Nepali Foreign
Minister Prakash Chandra Lohani said today.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have narrowed down many of the differences in
their respective detailed project reports for the Pancheshwar
project especially its designed generating capacity, Lohani was
quoted by the Kathmandu Post daily as saying today.
</P>
<P>
The agreement on the project's size came during a two-day
meeting of the Nepal-India high-level task force for the project
held here over the weekend, Nepali officials said.
</P>
<P>
India's acceptance of the concept of maximizing the project's
benefit was seen as a concession for Nepal, which has been
proposing to design the project to its full generating potential
of 6,480 megawatts.
</P>
<P>
Earlier India insisted that a smaller project with the
generating capacity between 2,000 to 4,000 megawatts be built
under the consideration of giving more emphasis to the project's
irrigation function.
</P>
<P>
The Pancheshwar project is the centerpiece of a bilateral
treaty between the two neighbors on the integrated development of
the Mahakali border river, about 450 kilometers west of Kathmandu.
</P>
<P>
The treaty was signed at the prime minister level in New Delhi
in March 1996 and ratified by the Nepali Parliament six months
later.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that the two governments will exchange the
documents of the Mahakali Treaty's ratification during Indian
Prime Minister I. K. Gujral's visit to Nepal later this week.
</P>
<P>
Nepali officials said the two countries will have to finalize a
joint detailed report for the Pancheshwar project within six
months after the exchange of the ratification documents, formally
bringing the treaty into force.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
