<HEADLINE> Some 300 Mon Rebels Surrender to Myanmar Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 3 (Xinhua) -- More than 300 ethnic Mon rebels
have surrendered to the Myanmar authorities and handed over some
1,700 pieces of arms and ammunition at a camp near the
Thai-Myanmar border, local newspaper the Bangkok Post reported
today.
</P>
<P>
A ceremony for the surrender was held on Monday in the last Mon
stronghold in Chong Chee in Myanmar, an unofficial border pass
close to the Thai border district of Bang Saphan in Prachuap Khiri
Khan province, report said.
</P>
<P>
The 300 rebels, under the command of Aung Hlaing, broke away
from the mainstream New Mon State Party (NMSP) nearly two years
ago, denouncing NMSP leader Nai Shwe Kyin for signing a ceasefire
agreement with the government, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
However, about 700 family members of the 300 rebels did not
follow them and moved into the Bang Saphan district as the fate of
the surrenders remained unclear.
</P>
<P>
There are an estimated four million ethnic Mons in Myanmar who
were seeking autonomy for the Mon state. Thailand currently also
accommodates 17,000 Mon refugees.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
