<HEADLINE> Liberals to Form Canada's Majority Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Canada's ruling Liberal Party is to
form a majority government, CBC Television reported today.
</P>
<P>
At press time, Jean Chretien's Liberal Party has won 154 seats
of a total of 301.
</P>
<P>
The party led others in the preliminary results of the poll
which has just closed.
</P>
<P>
It was followed by the Progressive Conservative, the Reform,
the New Democratic Party and the Bloc Quebecois.
</P>
<P>
Voting began at 9:30 a.m. (local time) and closed at 9:30
p.m. The final results are expected to be released at 11 p.m.
</P>
<P>
Across the country, about 19 million voters were eligible to
choose among the 1,672 candidates running. Many of them have said
that they would not come out and vote at the end of the five-week
campaign.
</P>
<P>
Chretien called the election one and half years early,
primarily because polls showed he would win. But he bungled at the
start, launching the five-week campaign as the worst flood of the
century ravaged the province of Manitoba.
</P>
<P>
In the last election held on October 25, 1993, the Liberals won
177 seats in the outgoing 295-member parliament. 
</P>
