<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central China Province Seeking Overseas Cooperation In Ecology </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Hunan Province in central China is
seeking enhanced overseas cooperation in environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
The province used 110 million US dollars of overseas capital
from international nature protection organizations by the end of
1996, and begun to witness good results from the improved
environment.
</P>
<P>
Farmers in Zhakou Township of Lixian County now live in a
better environment thanks to a 100,000-Australian-dollar project
financed by the Worldwide Fund for Nature, Australia.
</P>
<P>
The township was typical of the Dongting Lake areas, and
farmers there earned their living by exploiting small coalpits and
other resources. As a result, the lake areas have been polluted by
waste water and slags.
</P>
<P>
The fund has helped local farmers raise centipedes, plant trees
on waste hillsides, and tighten control over random mining, to
balance economic development and the eco-system.
</P>
<P>
The province is expected to receive 12 million Deutsche marks
from Germany to protect the Dongting Lake by building up the
Yangtze River shelterbelt.
</P>
<P>
Hunan Province has worked out a biological protection program
with Finland, which is to start in this autumn, with part of the
capital coming from the Federation of Nature and National Parks of
Europe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970603.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
