<HEADLINE> Thai Government to Aid Laid-off Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The Thai Labor and Social Welfare
Ministry is planning to set aside a budget of 100 million baht (4
million US dollars) to ease the hardship of workers laid off
recently due to the economic slowdown.
</P>
<P>
The funds will be used as loans extended to the estimated
20,000 laid-off workers around the country, most are unskilled
ones, from the sluggish sectors to help them start their own
businesses or improve skills.
</P>
<P>
Providing loans to laid-off workers is one of the government's
measures to cope with unemployment. Another measure is to provide
training to those unskilled workers to improve their skills to
meet the market needs.
</P>
<P>
Local newspapers said that the ministry is keeping a close
watch on 79 of the 1,700 high-risk businesses in garments,
textile, shoes, toys, frozen food and jewelry sectors.
</P>
<P>
However, officials from the ministry have expressed confidence
that the ministry could control the unemployment situation in the
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
