<DOCNO> XIE19970603.0251 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Large Amount of Amphetamines Smuggled into Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 3 (Xinhua) -- About 12 to 18 million tablets of
amphetamines have been smuggled into Thailand in the past six
months, according to a report issued by the Thai Narcotics Control
Board (ONCB).
</P>
<P>
Today's local press quoted the report as saying that the
majority of the drug smuggled into Thailand come from Myanmar. Mae
Sai district of northern Thailand's province of Chiang Rai was
found to have the highest rate of amphetamine smuggling with about
one million tablets a month coming across the Myanmar-Thai border
into Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The report said the production of amphetamines in Myanmar
increased following drug warlord Khun Sa's surrender to the
Myanmar government.
</P>
<P>
It said his surrender caused small ethnic groups, which were
once under Khun Sa's control, to turn to the production of
amphetamines for sale to Thailand because the trade has become
more lucrative than heroin production.
</P>
<P>
The report said manufacturers in Myanmar have begun to use Laos
as a transit route to smuggle the drug into Thailand following
increase checks along the Thai-Myanmar border.
</P>
<P>
The ONCB believed that amphetamine tablets are being produced
along the Lao-Thai border. The report also said some amphetamines
are produced in Koh Kong in Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
The report said that because of the lucrative nature of the
business and because more people have turned to amphetamines, more
traffickers have joined the trade.
</P>
<P>
The ONCB proposed that the Thai government seek cooperation
from neighboring countries to crack down on manufacturers and
smugglers of the drug.
</P>
<P>
It also suggested that the Thai government launch a public
awareness campaign to warn people about the danger of amphetamines
abuse.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
