<HEADLINE> Taihu Lake Economic Belt Thriving </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The economic belt surrounding
Taihu Lake in the Yangtze River Delta is thriving and has become
one of the country's fastest-growing areas.
</P>
<P>
The belt comprises the cities of Suzhou, Wuxi, Changzhou, and
Huzhou in Jiangsu and Zhejiang provinces, long been famed as the
"prosperous hometown of fish and rice."
</P>
<P>
Accounting for only 0.19 percent of China's total areas and 1.1
percent of its population, the lake belt, however, chalked up 3.6
percent of the country's total GDP in 1996, 2.9 percent of retail
sales, and 7.8 percent of foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
Per-capita GDP in the belt surpassed 10,000 yuan in 1996,
statistics indicate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
