<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia to Normalize Relationship With OSCE </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslav Prime Minister Radoje
Kontic has said that his country hoped to normalize the
relationship with the Organization for Security and Cooperation in
Europe (OSCE).
</P>
<P>
Kontic made the remarks in an interview with the Austrian
newspaper Die Presse, the Yugoslav news agency Tanjug reported on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
He said that there is no reason to deny Yugoslavia its
membership in the OSCE and there would be no real security and
cooperation in Europe without Yugoslavia's participation.
</P>
<P>
The OSCE suspended Yugoslavia's membership in 1992 due to the
Bosnia War in the former Yugoslav region.
</P>
<P>
As for the government's development plan, Kontic said
Yugoslavia has four strategic tasks, which are "to build a
modernized and democratic country, to return to the international
community, to set up an open and vigorous market economy and to
promote the people's living standard and social security."
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia has made great achievements in stablizing and
restoring the country's economy, Kontic added. 
