<HEADLINE> ESCAP Calls for Upgrading Transport to Boost Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BANGKOK, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations' Economic and
Social Commission for Asia and the Pacific (ESCAP) has urged all
the related countries in the Greater Mekong Subregion (GMS) to
upgrade the transport system to boost tourism.
</P>
<P>
The call was made by ESCAP to representatives of tourism
organizations from Myanmar, Cambodia, Laos, Thailand, Vietnam, and
China's Yunnan province, who met here recently to work out ways to
cooperate in developing the subregional tourism.
</P>
<P>
Except in Thailand and China, road conditions within the
Subregion are extremely poor, which limit tourists to short
routes, ESCAP said in a report.
</P>
<P>
Airports or airfields in the Subregion, which play an
important role in tourism development, also needed to be upgraded,
it said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, ESCAP suggested that the six related countries ease
immigration restrictions for cross-border travel and develop a
single travel permit for touring within the Subregion.
</P>
<P>
In addition, ESCAP pointed out that although railway travel is
possible in Myanmar, Thailand and china's Yunnan province and
Vietnam, cross-border railway links are only available between
Yunnan and Vietnam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
