<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Congratulates New French Premier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi
and leftist party leader Massio D'Alema today congratulated the
newly-elected French socialist Prime Minister Lionel Jospin.
</P>
<P>
Jospin was appointed today by center-right President Jacques
Chirac as new prime minister after his Socialist party won the
snap election called by Chirac.
</P>
<P>
"I want to send you warmest congratulations on your appointment
as prime minister of the French Republic, in the name of the
Italian government and on my own behalf," Prodi said.
</P>
<P>
Prodi, who leads a center-left coalition government in Italy,
voiced his hope for closer bilateral ties and a more integrated
Europe during Jospin's term.
</P>
<P>
Continuing to strengthen the European Union (EU) is the only
way to guarantee stable and solid economic growth and greater
security in the continent, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The process of completing economic and monetary union and
expanding to include new member states lies in such a context,"
Prodi said.
</P>
<P>
But analysts believe that a Socialist cabinet in France is not
a good omen for the European Economic and Monetary Union (EMU),
which is to launch a single European currency, the euro, by the
end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
The victory of the Socialists, who are sceptical of the EMU and
opposed to Chirac's austerity policies to qualify France for the
EMU, makes France unlikely to be able to meet the budget deficit
criteria set down by the EMU.
</P>
<P>
The single currency requires a budget deficit ceiling of less
than three percent of the GDP.
</P>
<P>
Leader of Italy's largest left-wing party, Massio D'Alema, also
hailed the election victory of Jospin today, saying people in
Europe favor leftist governments, the ANSA news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The leader of the former communist Democratic Party of the
Left, the largest partner in Italy's ruling center-left Olive Tree
coalition government, pointed out that 13 of the 15 member states
of the EU now had leftist governments.
</P>
<P>
"The clear success of Lionel Jospin, after the earlier one of
Tony Blair (in Britain), is a sign that the European people want
it to be left, with its values, its ability to govern and its
sense of responsibility, to steer the process of European
unification," D'Alema said.
</P>
<P>
He said he felt "satisfaction not only for the left and for
France, but also for his personal success which rewards his gifts
of intelligence, seriousness and likableness."
</P>
<P>
He added that his party was working on an orientation document
for discussion at the conference of European socialist parties in
Malmoe, Sweden, on Wednesday, Thursday and Friday, according to
ANSA.
</P>
<P>
The document seeks to find ways to create a Europe with the
right policies for growth and jobs, for a more equitable welfare
system and greater involvement of the European parliament, D'Alema
said.
</P>
<P>
Party officials said the election of Jospin following that of
Blair increased the importance of the Malmoe meeting, which comes
shortly before the concluding sessions of the Inter-governmental
Conference for the revision of the EU's Maastricht Treaty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
