<HEADLINE> EU Urged to Accept Thai Products Inspection Standards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Thailand is pressuring the European
Union (EU) to accept Thai inspection standards for goods exported
to the EU, according to a local press report today.
</P>
<P>
A Thai delegation will raise the issue at a Thai-EU joint
committee meeting on Thursday and Friday in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
The Thai side wants the EU to accept the quality and standard
of Thai products inspected and passed by Thai officials, a Thai
Foreign Ministry source was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Thai delegation also plans to joint three
economic cooperation programs established by the EU a few years
ago under its Asian strategy: the Asia eco-best program that
promotes investment in environmental technology; the Asia invest
program aimed at promoting two-way investment; and an economic
research and development program for emerging economies.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the source said, the Thai delegation would
raise the touchy issue of the EU's decision to cut the generalized
system of preferences on Thai shrimp exports to the EU.
</P>
<P>
The EU is Thailand's fourth-largest trading partner after
ASEAN, the United States and Japan. Two-way trade last year was
500 billion baht (20 billion US dollars), with Thailand recording
a trade surplus of about 50 billion baht (2 billion US dollars).
</P>
