<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rioters Burn Sub-district Office in West Java, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 3 (Xinhua) -- A mob that were disappointed with
the vote counting, Monday morning vandalized and set ablaze the
Malanggah sub-district office of Serang, Indonesia's West Java
province, reports reaching here today said.
</P>
<P>
Serang police chief Capt. Abdul Rochim confirmed the incident
last night, saying that no election documents were burned. Ballot
boxes and other election documents had previously been sent to the
district office, he added.
</P>
<P>
"Police are still searching for the arsonists," he said.
</P>
<P>
In Jakarta, the military is to begin today the withdrawal of
soldiers deployed since April to reinforce security in the capital
city during campaigning and the election, military sources said.
</P>
<P>
"There is no longer a reason to maintain such a strong security
presence here because Jakarta has now returned to normal," said
head of the Jakarta military command Major General Sutiyoso.
</P>
<P>
The military deployed about 7,700 troops to assist city police
in assuring security during the 27-day campaign period and
election day on May 29.
</P>
<P>
According to provisional results, the ruling party Golkar has
headed for another landslide victory with more than 74 percent of
the votes, the United Development Party (PPP) followed with about
23 percent and the Indonesian Democratic Party (PDI) only obtained
more than 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
The three parties are vying for 425 seats of the 500-member
house of representatives. The remaining are reserved for the armed
forces whose members do not vote.
</P>
<P>
A total of 124.7 million people were eligible to vote in the
election, the sixth one in the country since 1971.
</P>
<P>
The final results of the election will be released in the
middle of this month.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
