<DOCNO> XIE19970603.0268 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong's Return Expected to Boost Inland Growth (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong can provide a broader
array of intermediary financial services to inland areas after its
return to the motherland in July, a senior banking official from
Hong Kong said here today.
</P>
<P>
For years, Hong Kong has been a bridgehead for inland area's
cooperation and exchange with the rest of the world, Andrew
L. T. Sheng, vice-chairman of the Hong Kong Monetary Authority
(HKMA), said at a recent international seminar on reform and
development in Guizhou, a less-developed province in the southwest.
</P>
<P>
Official figures show that trade between the inland areas and
Hong Kong made up nearly half of the inland's total with the
outside world last year.
</P>
<P>
Date provided by HKMA show that Hong Kong's direct investment
in the inland has totaled 770 billion Hong Kong dollars, the
largest among all overseas investors.
</P>
<P>
Besides close trade ties, relations in the financial sector
have been growing even more rapidly between Hong Kong and the
inland, Sheng said.
</P>
<P>
More than half of the banks registered in Hong Kong had opened
branches or representative offices in the inland by the end of
last year. Some of them have been approved to deal in business in
RMB yuan by the People's Bank of China, the central bank.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, more inland banks have set up subsidiaries in Hong
Kong. The Bank of China Group now has the second largest
subsidiary network in Hong Kong and is Hong Kong's third
note-issuing bank.
</P>
<P>
The China Construction Bank, the Agricultural Bank of China,
and the Industrial and Commercial Bank of China, the other three
state-owned banks in the inland, have also obtained licenses for
issuing notes in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong has become a major pipeline through which syndicated
bank loans are arranged for the inland. Estimates say that 90
percent of the syndicated loans to the inland are arranged by Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that banks in Hong Kong had 298 billion Hong
Kong dollars in liabilities to inland banks while having 358
billion Hong Kong dollars in creditor's rights.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970603.0269 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong's Return Expected to Boost Inland Growth (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Sheng also said that currently 50 companies listed on the Stock
Exchange of Hong Kong are controled by inland investors. The
companies account for six percent of the stock market
capitalization.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the market capitalization of H shares issued
by inland companies has exceeded 36 billion Hong Kong dollars.
Hong Kong investors have also participated actively in trading of
B shares issued by inland firms through the stock exchanges in
Shanghai and Shenzhen. B shares are reserved for overseas
investors.
</P>
<P>
Sheng said that the HKMA is fully confident about the
continuation of Hong Kong as an international financial center.
</P>
<P>
The economies of Hong Kong and the inland areas are
complementary to each other and this will benefit Hong Kong as a
financial center, he said.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank predicts that in the next ten years China's
inland areas will need 800 billion US dollars for construction of
basic facilities necessary for further economic growth.
</P>
<P>
In the process, Hong Kong will provide a wider scope of
intermediary financial services for the inland areas, especially
for the resource-rich central and western parts, Sheng said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Hong Kong's direct investment in the inland has
extended beyond the Pearl River delta, which is in nearby
Guangdong Province, and expanded to the interior areas.
</P>
<P>
More investment from Hong Kong is now being poured into
projects in the infrastructure, such as energy and transportation,
Sheng said.
</P>
<P>
He also pointed out that Hong Kong can help the inland develop
the financial sector, as it has an advanced financial market of
its own, a diversity of financial products, and experienced
professional and management personnel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
