<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fiat Company Wins La Fenice Contract </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 2 (Xinhua) -- A construction company of the Fiat
Group, Impregilo, has been awarded the contract to rebuild the
historic La Fenice opera house destroyed by fire last year, The
ANSA news agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Designers of the winning bid are internationally-known
architects Gae Aulenti and Antonio Foscari, together with
Margherita Petranzan.
</P>
<P>
Aulenti and Foscari restored the Fiat-owned Palazzo Grassi, a
popular museum in Venice.
</P>
<P>
The Impregilo bid reportedly defeated the Bologna-based CCC
firm on aesthetic grounds and because of the relatively low
maintenance costs proposed.
</P>
<P>
La Fenice was completely gutted by fire on the night of January
29, 1996.
</P>
<P>
After considering suggestions that La Fenice be rebuilt as a
modern opera house, a team of experts ruled that the theater
should be recreated just as it was on the original site in Venice.
</P>
<P>
Prosecutors investigating the blaze are pursuing two lines of
inquiry, both of which carry arson charges. In one hypothesis, the
fire was started by the mafia as part of a campaign to sow terror
by striking famous Italian monuments, ANSA said.
</P>
<P>
On May 22, however, Judge Felice Casson ordered the arrest of two
electricians who had been working with a crew inside the theater at
the time of the fire.
</P>
<P>
But, Casson is continuing to look into the possibility of a
mafia crime, said ANSA. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
