<HEADLINE> Czech President Appoints New Ministers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, June 2 (Xinhua) -- President of the Czech Republic
Vaclav Havel on Monday appointed three new ministers, on the
proposal of Prime Minister Vaclav Klaus.
</P>
<P>
They are Finance Minister Ivan Pilip, Industry and Trade
Minister Karel Kuhnl and Education Minister Jiri
Grusa. Respectively, they used to be the education minister and
the ambassadors to Britain and Germany.
</P>
<P>
Havel on the same day also accepted the resignation of former
Finance Minister Ivan Kocarnik and Industry and Trade Minister
Vladimir Dlouhy.
</P>
<P>
The reshuffle stems from the country's economic difficulties,
and is the biggest reshuffle since Klaus formed his cabinet in
July 1996.
</P>
<P>
The opposition parties are planning to raise a no-confidence
motion against the government at a coming conference of the
Chamber of Deputies (lower house of the parliament). 
</P>
