<HEADLINE> Kuerten and Arazi Make SuRprise Hits at French Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Brazilian surprise-package Gustavo
Kuerten and Morocco's hero Hicham Arazi kept their giantkilling
exploits at the French Open on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The two unlikely quarter-finalists continued their remarkable
run at the Championships -- Kuerten completing a five-set win over
dangerous Ukrainian Andrei Medvedev and Arazi putting out
seventh-seed Marcelo Rios of Chile.
</P>
<P>
The wins put the South American into a showdown with Russia's
titleholder Yevgeny Kafelnikov, while Arazi now faces the 1993 and
1994 champion Sergi Bruguera.
</P>
<P>
Bruguera, who is seeded 16, put out the second-seed and 1989
champion Michael Chang 3-6, 6-4, 6-3, 6-4 while Galo Blanco,
ranked a modest 111th, in the world rankings made sure Spain had
two players in the last eight by defeating Petr Korda of the Czech
Republic 1-6, 6-1, 7-5, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
Blanco, 20, now plays Patrick Rafter, who won the
all-Australian clash against his old mate Mark Woodforde 6-2, 5-7,
6-1, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
Arazi is the first Moroccan ever to reach the quarter-finals of
a Grand Slam tournament, Kuerten the first Brazilian to reach the
last eight at Roland Garros since Tomas Koch in 1968 and Rafter
the first Australian since Peter McNamara in 1982. 
</P>
</TEXT>
