<HEADLINE> UK PM Promises 3 Billion Pound to Create Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 2 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
today promised a better future for Britons by pumping into 3
billion pound (4.9 billion U.S. dollars) to create jobs for those
unemployed who only rely on welfare.
</P>
<P>
In his first speech outside parliament since he took powed on
May 2, Blair said, "To be a citizen of Britain is not just to hold
its passport, it is to share its aspirations, to be part of the
British family."
</P>
<P>
He said the government's maiden budget, to be presented to
parliament later in the day, would invest three billion pound to
put 250,000 unemployed people back to work, financed by taxing the
excess profits of privatized utilities.
</P>
<P>
"It will be the Welfare to Work budget. This will be the
Welfare to Work government," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
The government plans to get a total of 5 billion pound to
reform welfare and education by a windfall tax to utilities and
lottery companies.
</P>
<P>
Blair said the basis of the modern civic society "is an ethic
of mutual responsibility or duty. It is something for something. A
society where we play by the rules."
</P>
<P>
He said the government, in drawing up ambitious plans to reform
Britain's 90 billion pound a year welfare state, would not fall
into the trap of short-termism.
</P>
<P>
"This is a government with a new sense of purpose. A government
that believes in giving everyone the chance to succeed and get on
in life. It is a government that has a will to win," the prime
minister added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
