<HEADLINE> Nigeria Takes Action in S. Leone at Invitation, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The Nigeria Television Authority
said tonight the military intervention by Nigeria-led
multinational troops in Sierra Leone this morning was at the
invitation of the country's ousted President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
The attack by the west African peacekeeping force on the
coupists who a week ago overthrew the civilian government led by
Kabbah has won wide welcome from the international community, the
national TV station reported.
</P>
<P>
The action was commended by African leaders at the summit of
the Organization of African Unity (OAU) currently being held in
Harare, Zimbabwe, it said.
</P>
<P>
Those speaking in favor of Nigeria and its allies include
United Nations Secretary-General Kofi Annan, OAU
General-Secretary Salim Ahmed Salim and Zimbabwean President
Robert Mugabe, it added.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, this is Africa's first regional
military intervention to crack down upon rebellious actions that
usually lead to crisis and instability.
</P>
<P>
Today's attack followed the failure last night to strike a
peace agreement between west African countries, Britain, and
Major Johnny Paul Koroma, leader of the coupist Armed Forces
Revolutionary Council set up in the wake of the May 25 coup that
toppled the elected government.
</P>
<P>
Koroma last night announced a 20-member cabinet, triggering
off the military intervention.
</P>
<P>
Intense fighting is going on in Freetown, capital of Sierra
Leone. The west African multinational troops have taken under
control the Lungi International Airport near Freetown and made it
a base for receiving reinforcements. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
