<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreigners Traveling to US Up Last Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 2 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Commerce Department
reported today that people traveling to the United States in 1996
were 7 percent more than in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The boom followed three straight years when the number of
travelers declined.
</P>
<P>
The report said that Canada had the largest number of arrivals
to the United States last year, topping 15 million. The department
estimates more than 18 million Canadians will visit the United
States between now and the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
More than 9 million people from Mexico traveled to the United
States last year, the second largest.
</P>
<P>
Japan remained on top as the most frequent travelers overseas,
with arrivals surpassing 5 million.
</P>
<P>
The report said that in the last 30 years tourism receipts in
the U.S. have increased more than 3,400 percent, jumping from 12
billion dollars in 1965 to 23 billion in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. tourism industry is the largest in the world, with
growth rates of travel receipts advancing at four times the
international average rate, the report said.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Commerce Secretary William Daley said today that
international travelers aid the country by contributing billions
of dollars to wide-ranging sectors of the economy and supporting
millions of jobs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
