<HEADLINE> U.S. Dollar Rises on Fears of Delay of Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar shot up against
the German mark and rose against most major currencies Monday on
fears of a delayed launching of the common European currency in
1999.
</P>
<P>
Investors began selling European currencies after France's
national elections Sunday. France promised to soften requirements
for joining the European Union's single currency.
</P>
<P>
In Germany, Chancellor Helmut Kohl and the central bank
continued their public battle over the government's plans to cut
debt by revaluing the central bank's gold reserves.
</P>
<P>
Hardest hit of the European currencies was the German mark,
which came under intense selling pressure. In New York, the dollar
settled at 1.7300 marks, up from 1.7063 on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Against the yen, the dollar rose to 116.58 yen from 116.22 yen
Friday. The pound fell against the dollar, dropping to 1.6359 U.S.
dollars from 1.6410 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The dollar was also boosted Monday by a stronger-than-expected
report from the U.S., saying growth in the U.S. manufacturing
economy was surprisingly robust in May.
</P>
<P>
Traders viewed the report as new evidence of strong economic
growth that could push the Federal Reserve to raise interest rates
next month to thwart inflationary pressures.
</P>
<P>
Other late-dollar rates in New York compared with late Friday:
1.4328 Swiss francs, up from 1.4129; 5.8320 French francs, up from
5.7595; 1,702 Italian lire, up from 1,692.50; 1.3757 Canadian
dollars, down from 1.3770.  
</P>
</TEXT>
