<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jury Convicts Oklahoma Bombing Suspect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Timothy McVeigh was convicted
Monday of blowing up the Oklahoma City federal building two years
ago.
</P>
<P>
McVeigh, a 29-year-old Gulf War veteran, could get the death
penalty for the April 19, 1995, bombing that killed 168 people and
injured hundreds more in the deadliest act of terrorism on U.S.
soil.
</P>
<P>
The federal jury that took more than 20 hours over four days to
convict McVeigh of all 11 counts of murder and conspiracy will
return to Denver federal courthouse Wednesday to decide if he
should pay with his life, according to news reports.
</P>
<P>
Cheers erupted outside the courthouse and at the bombing site,
where about 500 people gathered to hear the verdict. Victims'
relatives hugged and wept.
</P>
<P>
In Washington, U.S. President Bill Clinton said the verdict
heralded "a very important and long overdue day for the survivors
and families of those who died in Oklahoma City."
</P>
<P>
The verdict came just over two years after the explosion that
brought terror to the nation's heartland.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
