<DOCNO> XIE19970603.0295 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Sees no Change in Ties with France After Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 2 (Xinhua) -- The election of the Socialist
government in France will not influence the U.S.-French relations,
the White House said today.
</P>
<P>
White House Spokesman Michael McCurry told reporters that the
U.S. would "work closely" with a new French government, which is
to be formed by Lionel Jospin, the elected prime minister.
</P>
<P>
"We have a very close working relationship with the French
government. We continue to effectively explore our bilateral
concerns during periods of cohabitation, and we look forward to
working with the new government of Prime Minister Jospin," McCurry
said.
</P>
<P>
The French Socialist Party and its allies on the left scored a
decisive victory on Sunday, leaving French President Jacques
Chirac and U.S. President Bill Clinton in a similar position. Both
presidents have to work in tandem with their opposition.
</P>
<P>
"We've got an enduring interest that we explore through our
close and warm bilateral relationship with France...we would seek
a very active, productive, warm relationship with all elements of
the French government," McCurry stressed.
</P>
<P>
Late on Sunday, a U.S. State Department spokeswoman
congratulates France's Socialist Party for its victory and said
she looks forward to the establishment of the new government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
