<DOCNO> XIE19970603.0296 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Waigel to Seek Compromise with Bundesbank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 2 (Xinhua) -- German Finance Minister Theo Waigel
today said he would try to reach a compromise with the German
central bank before going ahead with his plan to revalue its gold
reserves in a bid to qualify for the single European currency.
</P>
<P>
But, speaking to reporters in the southern German city of
Munich, Waigel stressed that he would proceed with the plan even
without the assent of the central bank, known as the Bundesbank.
</P>
<P>
He said the main question now was whether the revaluation plan
could begin this year or next year, adding that he thought the
Bundesbank would be amenable to a revaluation in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The German government has triggered a feud with the Bundesbank
with the plan announced last month to revalue the bank's gold
reserves in line with market prices and to use the windfall to
reduce its debt to qualify for the planned single European
currency, the Euro.
</P>
<P>
The Bundesbank has warned that the government plan would
infringe on the bank's independence, and risk "a loss in trust in
the stability of the future European currency".
</P>
<P>
Defending the move, German Chancellor Helmut Kohl told a
meeting of bankers Monday in Switzerland that the gold revaluation
payout for Bonn would help Germany in its difficult struggle to
meet the strict debt and budget criteria for join the Euro at its
launching on January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
"There are historic chances, which, if wasted once, will not
come again in the near future," Kohl was quoted by German media as
saying.
</P>
<P>
"Naturally Germany wants to, and will meet the Maastricht debt
criteria," Kohl added.
</P>
<P>
Amid growing political tensions at home, Kohl Monday canceled
a speech due to be delivered Wednesday to a Western European Union
assembly in Paris because he wants to take part in a parliament
debate called by the main opposition Social Democratic Party (SPD)
on its request for Waigel's resignation.
</P>
<P>
Kohl will also have to tackle a standoff with the junior
partner in his ruling coalition -- Free Democratic Party -- over
whether to raise taxes to meet budget shortfalls for this year and
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The quarrel is said to have threatened Kohl's centre-right
ruling coalition and has already prompted the SPD to call for an
early election. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
