<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New York Stocks Mixed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 2 (Xinhua) -- Smaller-company stocks on Wall
Street rose to record levels for the seventh straight session, but
blue-chip shares fell today as some new economic data indicated
that inflationary pressures may be easing.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average fell 41.64 points to 7,289.40.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 3-to-2 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with its volume reaching 432.66
million shares, down from 533.46 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list fell 1.92 to 846.36, and
the NYSE's composite index fell 0.24 to 441.54.
</P>
<P>
The technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index rose 4.46 to
1,404.78.
</P>
<P>
The Russell 2000 rose 2.76 to 383.52. The American Stock
Exchange composite index, which is dominated by smaller companies,
rose 1.79 to 607.17.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that the economic pace seen in the first quarter
may be slowing enough to keep inflation in check without another
boost in interest rates by the Federal Reserve. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
